WEBVTT

00:21.313 --> 00:23.273
-All right.
-Okay. Hello.

00:23.357 --> 00:25.692
Stand by. We got speed.

00:25.776 --> 00:27.069
-You ready?
-Yeah.

00:27.152 --> 00:29.446
Now here's a little story
That I got to tell

00:29.530 --> 00:32.323
About three bad brothers
That you know so well

00:32.406 --> 00:34.910
It started way back in history

00:34.993 --> 00:36.411
-With Ad-Rock
-MCA

00:36.495 --> 00:37.579
-And me
-Mike D

00:52.261 --> 00:53.595
Who's your favorite Beastie Boy?

00:53.679 --> 00:55.806
I sort of identify
with bits of all of them really.

00:55.889 --> 00:58.642
I guess MCA resonates.

00:58.725 --> 00:59.643
Mike D.

00:59.726 --> 01:01.728
Ad-Rock is, like, big inspiration.

01:01.812 --> 01:03.230
When you listen to a group for that long,

01:03.313 --> 01:06.316
you go through phases
of who you feel you're more connected to

01:06.400 --> 01:07.651
at certain times in your life.

01:07.734 --> 01:09.027
My favorite is Mike D.

01:09.111 --> 01:11.864
He's really funny,
but in, like, a subtle way.

01:11.947 --> 01:14.366
Do you have a favorite Beasties video
over the years?

01:14.449 --> 01:18.120
Mine's actually an exercise video
that never came out.

01:18.203 --> 01:20.873
Call the number on your screen right now!

01:20.956 --> 01:23.876
MCA, I feel like, was the leader
of all of them. Kept them all together.

01:23.959 --> 01:25.752
He's the one that comes up
with all the crazy stuff.

01:25.836 --> 01:28.130
MCA definitely played a large part
in the world.

01:28.213 --> 01:30.215
Very influential man, a big heart.

01:30.299 --> 01:33.218
I always thought that Ad-Rock
kind of encapsulated the coolness.

01:33.302 --> 01:36.763
It's a word that is not really used
that much in these days,

01:36.847 --> 01:39.933
but I think it really suits me,
as well as these guys.

01:40.017 --> 01:41.018
It's "macho."

01:41.101 --> 01:42.644
It's a macho that we have.

01:42.728 --> 01:45.647
Because he's so honest.
He's, like, brutally honest.

01:45.731 --> 01:47.357
We're not very talented musically,

01:47.441 --> 01:49.568
so we figured we'd try all kinds
of different realms.

01:49.651 --> 01:50.527
Yauch.

01:51.028 --> 01:53.322
Yo, I'd just like to say, "What's up?"
to my grandma.

01:53.405 --> 01:56.116
Because it's all about the bass guitar
for me.

02:01.914 --> 02:05.250
Yo, hold up, wait up,
just sit down for a minute.

02:05.334 --> 02:06.668
It's not over yet.

02:07.419 --> 02:08.419
Go!

02:15.844 --> 02:17.846
Their music has just been so influential.

02:17.930 --> 02:20.015
The soundtrack of my life,
if you can call it that.

02:20.098 --> 02:22.184
It's the soundtrack of our lives.

02:22.267 --> 02:24.019
A lot of bands, they just break apart,

02:24.102 --> 02:26.688
and then they come back at the end.

02:26.772 --> 02:29.525
But they stayed together
the whole adventure.

02:29.608 --> 02:33.362
I can't stand it
I know you planned it

02:33.445 --> 02:35.572
I'mma set it straight, this Watergate

02:35.656 --> 02:38.700
I can't stand rockin' when I'm in here

02:38.784 --> 02:41.703
'Cause your crystal ball
Ain't so crystal clear

02:41.787 --> 02:44.998
So while you sit back and wonder why

02:45.082 --> 02:47.501
I got this fuckin' thorn in my side

02:47.584 --> 02:50.587
Oh, my God, it's a mirage

02:50.671 --> 02:53.465
I'm tellin' y'all, it's sabotage

02:55.884 --> 02:56.885
Yeah!

02:58.428 --> 02:59.721
All right.

03:03.308 --> 03:05.310
Yo!

03:07.729 --> 03:08.730
What's up?

03:09.398 --> 03:10.858
Brooklyn!

03:17.781 --> 03:19.449
Well, hi.

03:21.994 --> 03:22.995
Well...

03:23.871 --> 03:25.539
Hello, everyone.

03:28.500 --> 03:31.044
-Well, hi, everyone. I'm Adam.
-Hi, Adam.

03:31.128 --> 03:32.129
And I'm Mike.

03:32.212 --> 03:36.383
Also known as Michael Diamond or Mike D.

03:36.842 --> 03:39.094
And we're Beastie Boys from New York City.

03:43.182 --> 03:46.768
Now, tonight we're going
to tell you the story of three kids

03:46.852 --> 03:48.520
that met and became friends

03:48.604 --> 03:52.191
and did all kinds of crazy stuff
together for over 30 years.

03:52.983 --> 03:57.070
The two of us will do the best we can,
because one of us isn't here.

03:57.696 --> 03:58.780
Adam Yauch...

04:02.367 --> 04:04.828
who you also know as MCA.

04:05.871 --> 04:08.373
We lost him in 2012 to cancer.

04:08.457 --> 04:11.376
And when Adam died,
we stopped being a band.

04:12.127 --> 04:15.255
Yeah, it just felt too weird
to do the band without Yauch,

04:15.339 --> 04:19.218
because, well, I mean,
the band was his idea in the first place.

04:20.594 --> 04:23.138
So, although Yauch's not here with us,

04:23.805 --> 04:26.892
"What would Yauch do?"
is always on our minds.

04:27.643 --> 04:30.812
But trying to imagine what
Yauch would actually do is pretty hard,

04:30.896 --> 04:32.940
'cause he was very unpredictable.

04:33.023 --> 04:36.026
He was a wild card,
but we'll get to that later.

04:36.109 --> 04:37.653
The Beastie Boys have arrived.

04:37.736 --> 04:39.821
Always on the cutting edge of fashion.

04:39.905 --> 04:44.117
When they're not on the red carpet,
they are always at the shows in Paris.

04:44.201 --> 04:45.911
Look at the white dreads.

04:45.994 --> 04:49.790
The Beastie Boys are back
after a six-year absence.

04:49.873 --> 04:51.667
Guys, that's a long time.

04:51.750 --> 04:54.169
What have you been up to?
It's great to see you.

04:54.253 --> 04:56.255
-Hey!
-Actually, I know it sounds kinda funny,

04:56.338 --> 04:59.424
but we were actually
captured by Sasquatch.

05:00.092 --> 05:03.136
What we're gonna do right here
is go back.

05:03.637 --> 05:05.764
Way back. Back into time.

05:14.356 --> 05:20.112
Being a weird kid from, sorry, Mom,
a weird family, is just kind of weird.

05:20.195 --> 05:21.780
But it's also pretty lonely.

05:22.239 --> 05:23.907
One day, I heard this band The Clash.

05:31.748 --> 05:33.750
Not only did I love their music,

05:33.834 --> 05:37.546
but when I heard it,
I knew there'd be other weirdos out there.

05:37.629 --> 05:38.964
I just had to find them.

05:39.756 --> 05:42.176
I found my first other weirdo at school.

05:42.259 --> 05:44.303
His name is John Berry.

05:44.720 --> 05:48.891
One afternoon, we saw an ad in the back of
this free paper called The Village Voice.

05:48.974 --> 05:51.977
It was for a band that we loved
called the Bad Brains.

05:54.938 --> 05:56.732
And the Bad Brains were playing this show

05:56.815 --> 05:58.942
down at this place called
the Botany Talk House.

06:03.363 --> 06:04.823
So we go down to the club

06:04.907 --> 06:09.286
and there's, like, maybe all of 15 people
in the entire place,

06:09.369 --> 06:11.205
and they're all grown-ups.

06:11.288 --> 06:14.499
But there was one other kid our age there.

06:14.583 --> 06:15.667
And he looked really cool.

06:15.751 --> 06:18.795
He had this long trench coat on
from, like, a thrift store,

06:18.879 --> 06:20.047
he had combat boots,

06:20.130 --> 06:23.258
he had these homemade buttons
on his trench coat,

06:23.342 --> 06:25.886
and his name was Adam Yauch.

06:28.305 --> 06:33.519
So I met Yauch and Mike and John Berry
at a Misfits show in 1982.

06:35.020 --> 06:36.396
It might have been Circle Jerks,

06:36.480 --> 06:39.816
but I like the Misfits more, so I'm gonna
say that it was at a Misfits show.

06:39.900 --> 06:42.277
Now, somehow, me and my two friends heard

06:42.361 --> 06:45.113
that there were a bunch of kids
hanging out in a ladies' bathroom.

06:45.447 --> 06:46.990
So we walked in there

06:47.074 --> 06:52.538
and we found a bunch of super cool-looking
punk kids our age hanging out.

06:52.621 --> 06:55.332
And I actually recognized one of them,
Jill Cunniff,

06:55.415 --> 06:57.376
'cause we were
in fifth grade class together.

06:57.459 --> 06:59.169
And so she was my in.

06:59.253 --> 07:02.214
I also recognized one of the other kids
in the group,

07:02.297 --> 07:03.340
Kate Schellenbach,

07:03.423 --> 07:05.425
'cause we grew up
in the same neighborhood.

07:08.637 --> 07:10.681
Kate was just-- She was really cool.

07:10.764 --> 07:12.432
She was also smarter than we were.

07:12.516 --> 07:16.979
And she was into, I don't know, more
sophisticated, European kind of music--

07:17.062 --> 07:20.148
Just-- Sorry to interrupt, but just to say
that she was smarter than us--

07:20.232 --> 07:22.192
-I mean, Kate's very smart, but--
-Sure, it didn't take a lot.

07:22.276 --> 07:24.069
-Not that it's saying that much. Okay.
-But she was.

07:24.152 --> 07:25.153
-Fact.
-Correct.

07:26.488 --> 07:30.200
So, she was into cool bands
like Kraftwerk.

07:30.284 --> 07:33.704
And she lived in this loft on 14th Street
with her mom

07:33.787 --> 07:36.206
that was this big open old-style loft,

07:36.290 --> 07:39.251
and in the center of all of it
was her drum set.

07:41.962 --> 07:45.382
My first punk rock friend
was Dave Scilken. And he--

07:45.465 --> 07:47.885
That's him on the left.
And that's me on the right.

07:47.968 --> 07:49.845
So me and my best friend
in junior high school,

07:49.928 --> 07:51.763
we're playing basketball
outside of school,

07:51.847 --> 07:54.641
and we see this crazy-looking kid
with spiked hair and a trench coat

07:54.725 --> 07:57.436
walking down the street,
carrying a synthesizer.

07:57.519 --> 07:59.980
So we had to go over to talk to this kid.

08:00.772 --> 08:02.149
He was younger than us.

08:02.232 --> 08:05.194
He was in the sixth grade,
and he was cutting school.

08:06.236 --> 08:08.655
Now, let that sink in.

08:10.282 --> 08:12.951
You're 11 years old in the sixth grade.

08:14.411 --> 08:18.165
At that time, our main hangout
was at John Berry's apartment

08:18.248 --> 08:19.541
on 100th and Broadway.

08:19.625 --> 08:21.543
And that's where we'd play music.

08:21.627 --> 08:26.048
In the early '80s, everyone in our scene
was in some kind of band.

08:26.131 --> 08:29.760
And Yauch kept pushing us
to start a band with him.

08:29.843 --> 08:31.595
Now he already had a name for it:

08:32.135 --> 08:33.263
Beastie Boys.

08:36.475 --> 08:42.438
The band originally
was me, Kate, Adam Yauch, John Berry.

08:42.523 --> 08:43.899
The name stood for

08:43.982 --> 08:48.612
Boys Entering Anarchistic States
Towards Inner Excellence.

08:51.031 --> 08:53.367
The acronym alone makes no sense

08:53.450 --> 08:56.119
because "boys" is already
in the title of the band.

08:56.203 --> 08:58.580
So the name is ridiculous and redundant.

08:58.664 --> 09:01.875
And inaccurate,
because there was a girl drummer, Kate.

09:02.709 --> 09:06.004
So, our very first gig
was at John Berry's house,

09:06.088 --> 09:08.173
up where he lived, on the third floor.

09:09.341 --> 09:11.343
Yauch was turning 17.

09:11.426 --> 09:12.886
And Yauch's like, "You know what,

09:12.970 --> 09:15.472
I'm gonna have a party,
and we're gonna play at it."

09:20.394 --> 09:25.482
And then, when we go up to play,
somehow I got nominated to be the singer.

09:25.566 --> 09:29.194
Now, I was a super shy type of kid.

09:29.278 --> 09:31.029
I don't know why I ever agreed to this.

09:37.035 --> 09:40.372
I guess the main thing I remember is
probably, like, 10 or 12 kids in a room

09:40.455 --> 09:44.459
maybe 12 feet wide by 20 feet long
or something, just kind of, like,

09:44.543 --> 09:46.336
jumping up and down
and bumping into each other.

09:46.420 --> 09:49.548
But it was all basically, like,
friends having a good time.

09:53.886 --> 09:55.929
I wasn't in Beastie Boys back then.

09:56.013 --> 09:57.764
But I joined in 1983.

09:57.848 --> 10:00.475
John Berry wasn't into it anymore,
and so he quit.

10:01.435 --> 10:04.730
At that point, I was hanging out with
Mike and Yauch and Kate all the time.

10:04.813 --> 10:07.983
I guess since I was standing there,
I'm the new guitar player.

10:17.659 --> 10:20.329
We were a hardcore band,
but we kind of weren't.

10:20.412 --> 10:25.834
I mean, we were like Monty Python
as much as we were Black Flag.

10:28.462 --> 10:29.463
Introduce yourself.

10:29.546 --> 10:31.840
Yeah, yeah. So I'm Michael.
I'm in the Beastie Boys.

10:31.924 --> 10:35.427
My name is Kate. I'm a Capricorn,
and I have lint in my pocket.

10:35.511 --> 10:37.888
Now we're gonna get to an older,
more mature member.

10:37.971 --> 10:41.517
-Give us your name.
-My name's Ad, but you can call me Adam.

10:41.600 --> 10:45.854
And I'm just hanging out here on TV.
You know, your basic stuff.

10:45.938 --> 10:48.857
My name's Adam, as it says on my belt.

10:48.941 --> 10:50.943
Get a shot of Adam's belt if you can.

10:51.026 --> 10:53.320
How old are you? About 13, 14?

10:53.403 --> 10:55.030
-About.
-Yeah. Twelve, eleven.

10:55.113 --> 10:57.157
So, we're getting a little older now.

10:57.241 --> 10:58.951
We're no longer 15.

10:59.034 --> 11:00.118
We're 16.

11:01.078 --> 11:02.788
We were into all kinds of music.

11:02.871 --> 11:06.500
We listened to soul and punk
and rap and reggae.

11:06.583 --> 11:09.294
Rap was hard to find back then
'cause there was only a few 12-inches out.

11:09.378 --> 11:11.588
But we wanted to switch up our style.

11:11.672 --> 11:13.924
So we were obsessed
with this stupid commercial

11:14.007 --> 11:16.176
for this ice-cream store called Carvel.

11:16.260 --> 11:20.138
Hello, I'm a Carvel celestial person
from outer space.

11:20.222 --> 11:21.890
My real name is Cookie Puss.

11:21.974 --> 11:23.559
And someone had the smart idea

11:23.642 --> 11:26.979
to record a super stupid
prank phone call song called

11:27.062 --> 11:28.230
"Cooky Puss."

11:35.070 --> 11:37.531
-Hello, Carvel.
-Yo, man. Cookie Puss there?

11:37.614 --> 11:38.615
Who?

11:39.783 --> 11:41.660
Cookie Puss.
I wanna speak to Cookie Puss, man.

11:41.743 --> 11:43.287
No. Nobody here by that name.

11:43.370 --> 11:45.330
Cookie O'Puss then. Cookie Chick...

11:45.414 --> 11:47.040
So, this guy Dave Parsons,

11:47.124 --> 11:50.294
he had this record store downtown
called the Rat Cage.

11:50.377 --> 11:54.089
We would cut school
to go hang out at this place, right?

11:54.173 --> 11:56.884
By this time,
Dave started a small record label.

11:56.967 --> 11:59.678
Put "Cooky Puss" out as a 12-inch, right.

11:59.761 --> 12:02.890
And then something happened
that we never thought would happen.

12:02.973 --> 12:06.268
DJs started playing our record in clubs.

12:06.351 --> 12:11.023
Then other people besides our 15 friends
actually heard our music.

12:11.106 --> 12:15.319
And one day, I went to visit a friend at
some weird high school temp job she had.

12:15.402 --> 12:17.738
And we heard that DJ Afrika Bambaataa

12:17.821 --> 12:20.991
was on a talk show or something
on some other floor in the building.

12:21.074 --> 12:22.492
And we got fuckin' psyched.

12:22.576 --> 12:25.829
And we ran down
and we snuck onto the TV set.

12:25.913 --> 12:27.748
And this is what happened next.

12:28.207 --> 12:29.958
I was wondering--
There's a song I really like

12:30.042 --> 12:32.878
called "Cooky Puss" by the Beastie Boys.
I was wondering if you ever heard of it.

12:32.961 --> 12:34.505
Yes, I heard of "Cooky Puss."

12:34.588 --> 12:38.592
I've gotten the record
through the rock pool. It's tough.

12:38.675 --> 12:39.676
Okay.

12:39.760 --> 12:41.470
Yeah, you like that--
Why do you like that one?

12:41.553 --> 12:43.931
Yeah, it's just a really funny song.
I heard it on the radio--

12:44.014 --> 12:47.809
It's got scratching and work on it?
Like that?

12:47.893 --> 12:49.728
It has a little bit of scratching on it.

12:49.811 --> 12:51.396
It's funky.

12:53.649 --> 12:54.942
Chapter 2:

12:55.025 --> 12:58.195
"All We Do Is Listen to Rap."

13:01.114 --> 13:03.784
In 1984, a song came out

13:03.867 --> 13:07.371
that would change the course
of our band forever.

13:07.454 --> 13:10.207
"Sucker MC's" by Run-DMC.

13:10.832 --> 13:15.337
Two years ago, a friend of mine
Asked me to say some MC rhymes

13:15.420 --> 13:17.881
So I said this rhyme I'm about to say

13:17.965 --> 13:20.926
The rhyme was def
A-then it went this way

13:21.009 --> 13:24.555
"Sucker MC's" was everywhere in New York
when it came out.

13:25.138 --> 13:26.557
You heard it coming out of cars,

13:26.640 --> 13:29.643
out of tape decks, out of pizza spots,
all over the city.

13:29.726 --> 13:31.854
Run-DMC was the shit.

13:31.937 --> 13:33.522
And we wanted to be just like them.

13:33.605 --> 13:36.233
I mean,
we studied every song, every lyric.

13:36.316 --> 13:38.902
We were lookin' at every picture,
tryin' to figure out their sneaks,

13:38.986 --> 13:40.487
their clothes, everything.

13:40.571 --> 13:44.783
We would study and repeat
all our favorite rap songs all day.

13:44.867 --> 13:47.536
Not that we felt we would ever be
a rap group or anything.

13:47.619 --> 13:49.997
But around this time,
we started writing our own rhymes.

13:50.080 --> 13:52.583
I think now we're gonna show
a little example

13:53.083 --> 13:56.128
that shows kind of where we were at
on the mic as MCs.

13:56.211 --> 13:59.131
Wait, we're not there yet.
You're jumping ahead there. Go back.

13:59.214 --> 14:01.216
-Am I jumping the gun?
-Turn around, Spike.

14:01.300 --> 14:03.802
-Really? Okay.
-All right. Time out.

14:03.886 --> 14:04.887
See, Spike?

14:04.970 --> 14:07.306
-We're definitely in the wrong place.
-The teleprompter...

14:11.476 --> 14:12.936
-All right. That's what I thought--
-Okay.

14:13.020 --> 14:14.771
-Here we go.
-Hey, hey, hey.

14:14.855 --> 14:19.318
We're back. We really-- We rehearsed this.
We practiced this, like, for real.

14:19.401 --> 14:21.987
I'm sorry. I fucked up the teleprompter.
Sorry about that.

14:22.070 --> 14:24.072
Teleprompter? I didn't even notice.

14:30.746 --> 14:31.747
Anyways.

14:32.748 --> 14:35.626
That's a good transition, you guys.
"Anyways."

14:36.376 --> 14:40.297
Around this time, we had this big show
coming up at Studio 54, right.

14:40.380 --> 14:44.051
Wait. The Studio 54.
You know, with, like, Brooke Shields.

14:44.134 --> 14:48.555
Okay. With, like, Baryshnikov,
Halston, Donna Summer.

14:49.139 --> 14:51.350
I didn't know if that was, like,
a call and response thing.

14:51.433 --> 14:53.810
-Yeah, no one really chimed in.
-I don't know. Anyway.

14:53.894 --> 14:58.190
Footnote about our show at Studio 54,
it was a Battle of the Bands and we lost.

14:58.273 --> 15:00.776
So, we had this show
coming up at Studio 54,

15:00.859 --> 15:02.819
and we wanted to play our song
"Cooky Puss."

15:02.903 --> 15:04.905
Now we never did it live before,
but we thought--

15:04.988 --> 15:07.366
We had this idea
to have a DJ do it with us.

15:07.991 --> 15:11.662
Our friend told us that he knew
about this NYU college kid that could DJ

15:11.745 --> 15:14.957
and wanted to be a rap producer
and had all this DJ equipment and stuff.

15:15.040 --> 15:18.544
But more important,
he had a bubble machine.

15:18.627 --> 15:21.880
Wait. Say what, Ad-Rock?
A bubble machine?

15:21.964 --> 15:24.800
Yo, homes. That's right, Mike D.
He had a bubble machine.

15:24.883 --> 15:25.884
Okay.

15:25.968 --> 15:29.137
So we went over to this guy's dorm room
to meet him.

15:29.221 --> 15:33.141
But when we get there, the door's opened
by this long-haired heavy metal guy

15:33.225 --> 15:36.562
with these weird leather zip-up gloves,
which totally freaked us out.

15:37.437 --> 15:38.939
This couldn't possibly be him.

15:39.022 --> 15:43.110
Now, he opens the door
to this teeny dorm room, right.

15:43.193 --> 15:46.029
And it's filled with, like, a huge PA

15:46.113 --> 15:48.949
and there's turntables
and all these drum machines.

15:49.032 --> 15:52.494
And yes, ladies and gentlemen,
a bubble machine.

15:53.495 --> 15:54.705
So what do we do?

15:54.788 --> 15:56.623
We hired him on the spot.

15:56.707 --> 15:58.375
And this is Rick Rubin.

16:03.547 --> 16:07.092
Now, at first, it seemed like
a weird fit with us and Rick Rubin.

16:07.176 --> 16:10.179
I mean, he's from Long Island
and we're from New York City.

16:10.262 --> 16:14.850
And also, Rick was into a bunch
of other stuff that we weren't into.

16:14.933 --> 16:16.685
Like wrestling and heavy metal.

16:16.768 --> 16:18.896
And we thought that shit
was kind of goofy.

16:18.979 --> 16:21.064
Rick seemed way older than us and--

16:23.817 --> 16:24.651
Well--

16:24.735 --> 16:26.403
We gotta work on the timing of that photo.

16:26.486 --> 16:27.571
-I mean--
-With the--

16:29.072 --> 16:31.909
Do we comment on the cable box or no?
I mean--

16:31.992 --> 16:34.536
-Everyone's thinking about it, yeah?
-Right.

16:34.620 --> 16:37.623
That was some high-tech shit for the time.

16:37.706 --> 16:41.668
They got the cable box,
the multi-line telephone. I mean--

16:42.711 --> 16:45.422
I mean, why can't it be like the old days,
with a pack of Salems

16:45.506 --> 16:47.799
and a fucking filled ashtray
next to your bed?

16:47.883 --> 16:48.884
I mean, right?

16:52.054 --> 16:55.641
Rick seemed way older than us,
and he seemed kind of more mature than us.

16:55.724 --> 16:57.809
And he had money to pay for things.

16:57.893 --> 17:00.145
But most of all, it was his confidence.

17:00.229 --> 17:02.439
Whatever he was into
was the thing to be into.

17:02.523 --> 17:04.107
And that could be infectious.

17:04.858 --> 17:06.193
You couldn't hang out with Rick

17:06.276 --> 17:09.069
and not be excited about
what he was excited about.

17:09.154 --> 17:10.570
So we kinda got into wrestling.

17:11.281 --> 17:12.324
Kinda.

17:12.866 --> 17:15.827
-And we definitely got into heavy metal.
-Definitely.

17:17.204 --> 17:19.079
-Definitely.
-Definitely.

17:19.915 --> 17:21.915
It only took a week for us
to go from thinking

17:22.000 --> 17:24.586
that the guy
with those zip-up gloves was goofy

17:24.670 --> 17:26.880
to thinking, "He's the coolest dude."

17:26.964 --> 17:28.799
He became part of our full-time crew.

17:29.800 --> 17:32.928
He kinda became, like,
this weird, cool older brother.

17:33.011 --> 17:35.097
And his dorm room
became our new headquarters.

17:35.180 --> 17:36.765
Like, our new Rat Cage.

17:36.849 --> 17:40.477
And every day, instead of going to school,
we'd go to Rick's dorm room to hang out.

17:40.561 --> 17:43.230
And we'd listen to records.
And then we'd go out to some club.

17:43.313 --> 17:45.566
And then we'd go to
Cozy Soup 'n' Burger to eat.

17:45.649 --> 17:48.068
And then we'd talk all about the night
and the music

17:48.151 --> 17:50.863
and all the music
we were gonna make together one day.

17:50.946 --> 17:53.782
After the Studio 54 show, we had a DJ.

17:53.866 --> 17:57.703
So we're like, "Fuck it. Let's try
to rap and do that as part of our show."

17:59.788 --> 18:03.250
So Rick joined our band
and became DJ Double R, of course.

18:03.333 --> 18:06.837
Our first shows with Rick,
we'd do, like, half as a hardcore band,

18:06.920 --> 18:10.549
and then we'd leave the stage
and we'd do the other half as a rap group.

18:10.632 --> 18:12.593
-B-E-A
-S-T-I-E

18:12.676 --> 18:15.012
We're the Beastie four
Rock shockin' the scene

18:15.095 --> 18:17.347
-I'm Master Adam Yauch
-And Slop the Rock

18:17.431 --> 18:19.600
-With Mike D
-Katie Schellenbach

18:19.683 --> 18:22.019
Now hip-hop, just don't stop

18:22.102 --> 18:24.146
You rock to the beat
Till it makes you drop

18:24.229 --> 18:27.065
Okay, okay. I think, you know--

18:28.317 --> 18:29.401
You get the--

18:31.403 --> 18:32.529
You get the idea.

18:32.613 --> 18:36.366
Most rappers hold their rhymes
in little pieces of paper, right?

18:36.867 --> 18:38.118
Isn't that a thing?

18:38.202 --> 18:39.953
It's one thing to hang out
with your friends

18:40.037 --> 18:42.122
and rap "Sucker MC's" all day long.

18:42.206 --> 18:46.460
But being on stage with an audience
and rapping our own rhymes,

18:46.543 --> 18:47.836
well, that was different.

18:47.920 --> 18:50.297
Now we didn't realize it,
but as time went on,

18:50.380 --> 18:54.510
the more we were hanging out with Rick
and starting to act like Rick,

18:54.593 --> 18:56.845
the less we were hanging out with Kate.

18:56.929 --> 19:00.390
And maybe even more so,
the less Kate was hanging out with us.

19:00.474 --> 19:02.893
I think our friends were very confused

19:02.976 --> 19:05.062
as why we were hanging out with Rick
all the time.

19:10.359 --> 19:12.653
Well, you know, a band's gotta eat.

19:15.656 --> 19:20.619
So around this time, Rick was producing
his first real rap song, "It's Yours,"

19:20.702 --> 19:22.496
for a rapper named T La Rock.

19:24.998 --> 19:29.127
Up until then, music for rap records
was mostly played by a band.

19:29.211 --> 19:31.880
It was played to sound, like,
funky and smoothed out

19:31.964 --> 19:33.465
so it would get on the radio.

19:33.549 --> 19:36.426
But "It's Yours" was just a rapper
and a drum machine.

19:36.510 --> 19:39.096
It was raw and punk in sound.

19:39.179 --> 19:40.347
So one night,

19:40.430 --> 19:45.602
Rick told us that he's gonna go meet
this guy, Russell Simmons, at Danceteria.

19:45.686 --> 19:48.647
We didn't know what Rick and Russell
were meeting about,

19:48.730 --> 19:52.067
but we are just psyched
to spy on them talking at the bar.

19:52.150 --> 19:55.612
'Cause this Russell guy
was not only Run-DMC's manager,

19:55.696 --> 19:58.282
but he was also DJ Run's brother.

19:58.365 --> 19:59.950
It wasn't like he was some guy that, like,

20:00.033 --> 20:02.828
knew some guy
that knew somebody connected to rap.

20:02.911 --> 20:04.246
Russell was rap.

20:04.329 --> 20:06.748
He was at the center
of the business of rap.

20:06.832 --> 20:09.126
Now when Russell left,
we were so psyched.

20:09.209 --> 20:11.086
We ran over to Rick and we were like,

20:11.170 --> 20:14.548
"Yo, yo, yo, yo, Rick.
You gotta tell us, like, everything.

20:14.631 --> 20:16.508
What did this Russell guy say to you?

20:16.592 --> 20:19.094
You gotta tell us
everything you guys talked about."

20:21.346 --> 20:23.098
Well, I mean, that's-- We were excited.

20:23.182 --> 20:24.141
That's pretty good.

20:24.224 --> 20:27.311
And that's what we sounded like
when we were, like, 16.

20:27.394 --> 20:30.022
So Rick told us
that Russell couldn't believe

20:30.105 --> 20:33.275
that not only "It's Yours" was made
by someone he'd never heard of,

20:33.358 --> 20:34.902
but it was made by a white guy.

20:34.985 --> 20:36.570
And Rick said that they hit it off

20:36.653 --> 20:39.990
and they hatched a plan
to start a record label, Def Jam.

20:40.073 --> 20:41.200
Wait a minute, wait a minute.

20:41.283 --> 20:44.578
Pay attention, hang up the phone
and watch this.

20:44.661 --> 20:45.996
Jam means record.

20:46.079 --> 20:48.332
Def is short for definitive.

20:48.415 --> 20:51.126
Definitely the best records
you could buy today.

20:51.210 --> 20:54.213
So def, so def, so def
It's a def jam

20:54.296 --> 20:58.008
And somewhere in those plans,
Rick told Russell about us.

20:58.759 --> 21:01.094
"Hey, I got these three white rappers.

21:01.178 --> 21:02.971
They're still in high school.

21:03.055 --> 21:06.808
I mean, they're punk rock,
but they love hip-hop even more.

21:06.892 --> 21:09.645
I mean, all they do is listen to rap."

21:16.860 --> 21:21.240
Russell Simmons immediately saw the
possibility in managing a white rap group.

21:21.323 --> 21:24.034
And within days,
we went to his office to meet with him.

21:24.117 --> 21:26.578
We think he's gonna have
this huge fancy office,

21:26.662 --> 21:30.499
but we go up there,
it's just, in reality, two small rooms.

21:30.582 --> 21:32.292
But what's kinda cool is,

21:32.376 --> 21:38.215
in one of the rooms there's fucking
Kurtis Blow, the King of Rap, right?

21:39.049 --> 21:43.804
And he's in Russell's office
trying to learn to break-dance.

21:43.887 --> 21:46.765
He's trying to spin on his head
for some reason.

21:46.849 --> 21:48.684
And not only that, I don't know if--

21:48.767 --> 21:51.270
Does anybody in here know
this crew Full Force?

21:52.563 --> 21:56.692
Well, he's surrounded-- He's surrounded
by the dudes in Full Force,

21:56.775 --> 22:00.070
who are watching him learn to break-dance.

22:00.153 --> 22:03.490
I mean, it was a crazy fuckin' scene,
is what we're trying to tell you guys.

22:04.825 --> 22:06.368
So when it came to confidence,

22:06.451 --> 22:09.204
Russell was even more next-level
than Rick.

22:09.746 --> 22:10.914
If you were in his orbit,

22:10.998 --> 22:15.002
you couldn't help but believe all the
awesome shit he said was gonna happen.

22:15.085 --> 22:17.963
In 1984, no one cared about rap music.

22:18.046 --> 22:19.590
I mean, it was barely on the radio.

22:19.673 --> 22:23.218
But everywhere Russell went
he'd be selling to everybody.

22:23.302 --> 22:26.805
"Run-DMC is gonna be the biggest artist
of our generation."

22:28.348 --> 22:31.643
"Rick Rubin. He's gonna be
the Phil Spector of rap.

22:32.853 --> 22:34.062
Beastie Boys?

22:34.146 --> 22:38.150
They're white B-boys and they're gonna be
the biggest group in the world."

22:39.568 --> 22:40.569
All right.

22:41.737 --> 22:43.405
Let's slow things down for a minute.

22:43.488 --> 22:45.407
We had just started rapping.

22:45.490 --> 22:47.784
I mean, we were mediocre at best.

22:47.868 --> 22:50.954
But Rick and Russell believed in us,
and that gave us confidence.

22:53.749 --> 22:58.170
And so they hooked it up for us
to go record our first rap song.

22:58.253 --> 22:59.671
It's called "Rock Hard."

23:02.049 --> 23:04.426
I don't know. It's not our finest moment
on the mic, okay.

23:04.510 --> 23:08.805
But you gotta understand, we love rap
music and we wanted to be rappers so bad.

23:08.889 --> 23:11.099
We wanted to be Run-DMC so bad.

23:11.183 --> 23:13.685
"First white B-boys, we don't regret.

23:13.769 --> 23:16.021
There's nothing wrong with your TV set."

23:17.814 --> 23:19.274
Russell Simmons wrote that line.

23:19.358 --> 23:21.610
And he kept telling us we had to say it
'cause it was great

23:21.693 --> 23:24.363
and how B-boy it was and punk
and all this other stuff.

23:24.446 --> 23:26.532
He also really wanted us to say,

23:26.615 --> 23:29.409
"I can play the drums, I can play guitar.

23:29.493 --> 23:32.496
Not just B-boys, we're real rock stars."

23:32.579 --> 23:34.206
And we went along with it.

23:34.289 --> 23:36.917
I mean, you're the legit dude in rap, man.

23:37.000 --> 23:40.087
You got fucking Kurtis Blow popping
and locking in your office and shit.

23:40.170 --> 23:43.006
I mean, if you think saying that's
gonna be fresh, fly, wild and bold,

23:43.090 --> 23:45.634
well, all right.
Turn me up in the headphones.

23:45.717 --> 23:47.469
Mike D, Ad-Rock, and MCA

23:48.053 --> 23:50.347
Not before long I could hear you say

23:50.430 --> 23:52.933
In a way, these boys got juice

23:53.016 --> 23:55.686
They're goin' off
You know they love to get loose

23:55.769 --> 23:57.896
Get loose, get loose

23:57.980 --> 23:59.356
Poose

24:00.107 --> 24:04.319
Now I would love to blame Rick
and Russell for the quality of the song,

24:04.403 --> 24:06.446
but that's all us on the mic.

24:06.530 --> 24:09.700
We wrote and said the rest of the lyrics
on that song.

24:09.783 --> 24:13.829
They wanted us to be a cartoon rap version
of an '80s metal band,

24:13.912 --> 24:18.041
but instead with Adidas shell toes
and tracksuits and shit.

24:18.125 --> 24:20.127
And we were all in.

24:20.210 --> 24:21.461
-Hell, yes.
-Right?

24:22.588 --> 24:23.630
For real.

24:25.591 --> 24:30.429
But it was decided at some point
that we had to kick Kate out of the band

24:30.512 --> 24:33.849
because she didn't fit
into our new tough rapper guy identity.

24:33.932 --> 24:35.559
Now how fucked-up is that?

24:36.685 --> 24:39.980
When Beastie Boys began,
the majority of our friends were girls.

24:40.063 --> 24:41.940
Like, the coolest girls.

24:42.024 --> 24:44.693
And it's really embarrassing
to think that we let them down.

24:45.444 --> 24:48.906
I mean, shit, maybe Kate would've quit
the band eventually,

24:48.989 --> 24:50.949
but it's just shitty
the way it all went down.

24:51.033 --> 24:54.161
See, up until then our band
was just more of a joke, you know?

24:54.244 --> 24:55.954
Something to do 'cause it was fun.

24:56.038 --> 24:58.707
Our big goal was to make each other laugh.

24:58.790 --> 25:02.711
But now we're with these Rick and Russell
guys, and they got big plans for us.

25:02.794 --> 25:04.546
It's like,
if Rick was the cool older brother,

25:04.630 --> 25:06.840
then Russell was, like,
the crazy-ass uncle.

25:06.924 --> 25:10.302
And we started hanging out every night,
all the time together.

25:10.385 --> 25:13.305
Going out to clubs.
Drinking screwdrivers, brass monkeys.

25:13.388 --> 25:16.225
And it was like this fucked-up fun family.

25:16.308 --> 25:20.187
Now, when you're young and drunk
and Russell Simmons is telling you

25:20.270 --> 25:23.357
that you're gonna be
the biggest rap group of all time,

25:23.440 --> 25:27.277
well, I guess you hear it enough,
you just start to believe that shit.

25:27.361 --> 25:30.614
And then some crazy shit happened.

25:33.492 --> 25:34.618
Spike.

25:35.369 --> 25:38.997
I'm sorry. Sorry about that.
There's supposed to be a cue here where--

25:39.081 --> 25:41.458
It was actually a bad joke anyways.
Keep going.

25:42.334 --> 25:44.002
It's gonna happen
or it's not gonna happen?

25:44.086 --> 25:45.295
Not tonight.

25:45.379 --> 25:47.506
This is the last show.
When is it supposed to happen?

25:47.589 --> 25:49.132
We didn't load it into the machine.

25:49.216 --> 25:51.176
Maybe we'll get it
before the end of the night.

25:51.260 --> 25:52.719
I'll get it. I'll get it.

25:52.803 --> 25:55.055
Well, it's a voice that goes,
"Crazy shit."

25:55.138 --> 25:58.433
And there's, like, a whole animation.
My friend Max Tannone did the-- Anyway.

25:59.059 --> 26:02.104
Hey, did you guys know that we opened
for Madonna on her very first tour?

26:03.188 --> 26:05.482
Well, we did. And the story of
how we opened for Madonna--

26:05.566 --> 26:06.817
Crazy shit.

26:09.111 --> 26:10.445
I got it.

26:12.155 --> 26:13.282
At any rate.

26:13.740 --> 26:17.494
So one day Russell Simmons gets a call
from Madonna's manager, Freddy DeMann.

26:17.578 --> 26:20.539
He calls and asks if Run-DMC
would like to open for Madonna

26:20.622 --> 26:21.832
on her first ever tour.

26:21.915 --> 26:25.085
And Russell said,
"Yes, they get 20 grand a show."

26:25.169 --> 26:27.921
Madonna's manager said, "Thank you, no."

26:28.005 --> 26:31.175
Madonna's manager calls Russell Simmons
back a couple hours later and he's like,

26:31.258 --> 26:34.553
"Hey, Russell. Do the Fat Boys wanna open
for Madonna on tour?"

26:35.220 --> 26:39.558
And he said, "Aw, man. The Fat Boys
are busy. They just can't do it."

26:39.641 --> 26:41.852
Russell never managed the Fat Boys.

26:43.562 --> 26:44.813
"But," he said,

26:44.897 --> 26:47.858
"I got these guys Beastie Boys,
and they'll do it for 500 bucks."

26:47.941 --> 26:49.401
And the next thing you know,

26:49.484 --> 26:52.112
we're in Seattle, Washington
at the Four Seasons hotel,

26:52.196 --> 26:54.573
getting ready to open for Madonna on tour.

26:55.407 --> 26:56.783
Remember that?

27:00.204 --> 27:04.458
So, before the tour,
we came up with a brilliant plan.

27:04.541 --> 27:08.504
What could we do that would
make all these people remember us?

27:08.587 --> 27:12.883
It certainly wasn't gonna be
our microphone mastery at the time.

27:12.966 --> 27:18.514
I mean, our big idea was that we should be
as rude and as awful as possible on stage.

27:18.597 --> 27:23.894
Yo! You better look out,
Detroit, Philly, Cincy, LA!

27:23.977 --> 27:25.229
We're coming to your town!

27:25.312 --> 27:26.772
I mean, if we just went up there

27:26.855 --> 27:29.358
and we just played
the two songs that we knew,

27:29.441 --> 27:30.817
and that's all we had at the time,

27:30.901 --> 27:33.570
and we just said,
"Thank you, everybody. Good night,"

27:33.654 --> 27:34.696
who would care?

27:34.780 --> 27:37.157
Instead, we'd be memorable.

27:37.241 --> 27:39.910
Memorable fuckin' jerks.

27:39.993 --> 27:41.787
We're real rock stars.

27:41.870 --> 27:44.164
I mean, everyone's there to see Madonna,

27:44.248 --> 27:46.416
and they for sure
don't give a fuck about us.

27:47.000 --> 27:49.461
But this is where
Rick's wrestling thing would come in.

27:49.545 --> 27:51.964
He wanted us
to be those wrestling villains

27:52.047 --> 27:54.800
screaming into the camera
at the side of the ring, like this:

27:54.883 --> 27:58.178
The only reason that we haven't done
a video yet is because as soon as we do,

27:58.262 --> 28:01.014
they're gonna have to change it
from MTV to Beastie TV.

28:01.098 --> 28:04.142
'Cause that's all they're gonna show
all day long, all night long.

28:04.226 --> 28:08.480
"The Beastie Boys. One of the finest
groups in music today." Right there.

28:08.564 --> 28:10.524
I think I'm wasting my breath
a little bit.

28:10.607 --> 28:12.109
Maybe I'm talking over your head.

28:12.192 --> 28:13.360
I think the interview's over.

28:13.443 --> 28:14.653
-Thank you very much.
-Me too.

28:18.323 --> 28:19.324
And so--

28:22.202 --> 28:24.246
And so every night on the Madonna tour,

28:24.329 --> 28:27.332
I would go out, front and center,
and I would do a speech like this.

28:29.209 --> 28:31.003
I'm the King Ad-Rock.

28:31.086 --> 28:33.422
And I'm the fucking king
of the Kings Theatre.

28:33.505 --> 28:34.631
And we're the Beastie Boys,

28:34.715 --> 28:37.342
and we're here tonight
to crush all competition.

28:37.426 --> 28:40.846
After we leave tonight you can
burn this motherfuckin' place down.

28:40.929 --> 28:43.098
'Cause y'all motherfuckers ain't shit.

28:48.687 --> 28:53.025
Just keep in mind
that this is who Adam was cursing out.

29:04.745 --> 29:06.788
It was, like,
a love-hate relationship type thing.

29:06.872 --> 29:10.375
You know, we hated them, they hated us.
It was, like, love.

29:11.418 --> 29:14.796
So we come home from tour,
and the very first thing we do

29:14.880 --> 29:19.551
is we go up to everyone and anyone
that'll hear it, and we're like,

29:19.635 --> 29:22.888
"Yo, yo, yo.
We were on tour with Madonna."

29:22.971 --> 29:25.349
It was the fucking
most awesome thing ever.

29:25.432 --> 29:27.935
And now we get home and it's official.

29:28.018 --> 29:29.311
We're a rap group.

29:31.563 --> 29:33.023
Really?

29:33.106 --> 29:34.900
-High five?
-Yeah.

29:34.983 --> 29:36.985
Yeah, it's coming back, Adam.
It's coming back.

29:38.570 --> 29:42.866
One night, Russell gets us a gig
at this club called the Encore,

29:42.950 --> 29:46.370
opening up for Kurtis Blow,
the King of Rap.

29:46.453 --> 29:48.455
So we were both--
We look at each other and we're like,

29:48.539 --> 29:53.001
"Yo, we're opening up for Kurtis Blow?
That's def."

29:54.127 --> 29:56.255
-Now--
-That's a direct quote, by the way.

29:56.338 --> 29:57.881
-Just so you know.
-Yeah. It is.

29:57.965 --> 30:02.094
Now the Encore is an all-black rap crowd.

30:02.177 --> 30:04.888
And we're the only white guys
in this place, right.

30:04.972 --> 30:08.308
And somehow, we decide it's a good idea

30:08.392 --> 30:11.436
to go out there
in a limo dressed like this.

30:15.649 --> 30:17.109
What's so funny?

30:18.610 --> 30:21.154
Yes, those are do-rags on our heads.

30:21.238 --> 30:22.948
So...

30:24.825 --> 30:29.496
So when we got on stage at the Encore
to play our song "Rock Hard,"

30:29.580 --> 30:32.040
they turned on all the lights, right,
in the house.

30:32.124 --> 30:34.668
Like, fluorescent lights,
like a fuckin' supermarket.

30:34.751 --> 30:37.671
And all these dudes in the audience
started screaming at us.

30:37.754 --> 30:40.591
"Yo, yo, Menudos. What's up?"

30:41.341 --> 30:42.885
"Menudo, I love y'all."

30:44.178 --> 30:46.054
Yeah, they called us "Menudo."

30:47.389 --> 30:50.934
Actually, I think it was "Menudos,"
like, plural.

30:51.476 --> 30:52.477
Yeah.

30:52.561 --> 30:54.938
So yeah, we dropped this look real quick.

30:56.023 --> 30:57.566
Chapter 3:

30:57.649 --> 30:59.902
"The Song that Changed Everything."

31:04.239 --> 31:06.408
So we started writing songs
in a different way.

31:06.491 --> 31:09.620
It wasn't just on a guitar, like,
verse, chorus, verse, chorus.

31:09.703 --> 31:12.706
Fucking around became
our creative process.

31:12.789 --> 31:14.458
It would go something like this.

31:14.541 --> 31:16.084
Mikey.

31:16.168 --> 31:17.920
We'd be walking down the street.

31:20.631 --> 31:21.882
This is how--

31:21.965 --> 31:23.008
Hey.

31:23.091 --> 31:24.801
This is how we'd walk down the street.

31:26.011 --> 31:27.930
-How you doing?
-What's up, man?

31:29.097 --> 31:30.265
We rehearsed.

31:30.974 --> 31:32.476
We'd be walking down the street, right.

31:32.559 --> 31:35.312
And we'd just start going back and forth
with little bits of records

31:35.395 --> 31:37.356
and stupid shit
we thought was real funny, right.

31:37.439 --> 31:40.609
Like, one of us would say a random lyric
from a song we loved like...

31:40.692 --> 31:42.236
Hold it now.

31:42.319 --> 31:45.489
And then another one would be like,
"Yo, that should be a song, like,

31:45.572 --> 31:48.742
he should say, 'Hold it now,'
and then we should have Slick Rick go"...

31:48.825 --> 31:49.868
Hit it!

31:49.952 --> 31:53.247
And then another one would be like,
"It should go"...

31:53.330 --> 31:54.831
Hey, Leroy!

31:54.915 --> 31:56.333
And that's the song.

31:57.626 --> 31:58.627
Now--

31:58.710 --> 32:03.090
And then we'd go into the studio
with that simple and stupid of an idea.

32:03.173 --> 32:04.591
And we'd make a song out of it.

32:04.675 --> 32:06.426
Yo, Leroy!

32:08.512 --> 32:10.931
Hold it now.
Hold it now, hold it now.

32:11.014 --> 32:11.849
Hit it!

32:11.932 --> 32:14.726
Like, Adam would be there
and he'd be tapping away, obsessed,

32:14.810 --> 32:16.937
on the pads of his DX drum machine.

32:17.020 --> 32:19.481
And when he was really psyched,
he'd take the headphones

32:19.565 --> 32:22.526
and he'd rip them off of his head,
throw them to the side, and he'd be like,

32:22.609 --> 32:25.279
"Yo, yo, yo, guys. Check this out."

32:25.362 --> 32:28.073
No, no, no. That's you, Mike.

32:28.156 --> 32:29.533
I was like this.

32:29.616 --> 32:31.451
Well, anyway, he made this--

32:31.535 --> 32:33.412
Honestly, I'm giving you props, Adam.

32:33.495 --> 32:36.164
He made, like, this
hot go-go, swing-type beat.

32:36.248 --> 32:39.293
But when Yauch and I heard that,
we were like, "Shit."

32:39.376 --> 32:43.255
But when that got layered
with this 808 beat,

32:43.338 --> 32:45.507
that changed everything.

32:45.591 --> 32:47.509
Hold it now.
Hold it now, hold it now.

32:47.593 --> 32:49.803
Hit it!

32:50.679 --> 32:53.682
So, the three of us were left
to our own devices

32:53.765 --> 32:56.018
and making music and loving it.

32:56.101 --> 32:58.687
Instead of trying to act and sound
like somebody else,

32:58.770 --> 33:00.189
like how we did on "Rock Hard,"

33:00.272 --> 33:01.815
now we were just being ourselves.

33:01.899 --> 33:04.526
Or at least a fantasy version
of ourselves.

33:05.444 --> 33:07.905
Rick came by the studio
and we played it for him.

33:07.988 --> 33:10.574
And he kinda flipped the fuck out.
He was like,

33:10.657 --> 33:13.118
"Hey, you guys. Don't change anything.

33:13.202 --> 33:16.205
It's great.
I want to play it for Russell.

33:16.288 --> 33:18.332
We need to just put this out."

33:18.415 --> 33:21.627
So, we're surprised, but we are psyched.

33:21.710 --> 33:24.922
Rick mixed it, making it sound bigger
and more professional.

33:25.005 --> 33:27.299
He made that 808 sound crazy.

33:29.134 --> 33:31.136
-Like that.
-Like that.

33:31.220 --> 33:34.389
You could hear it rattling the rear glass
on cars up and down the East Coast.

33:34.473 --> 33:36.975
It also detonated many a PA.

33:37.059 --> 33:40.395
We figured out how to piece together
different elements that we loved,

33:40.479 --> 33:44.274
like beats, samples, scratches,
and turn them into a song.

33:44.358 --> 33:46.068
Into a new style.

33:46.151 --> 33:49.404
Most importantly though,
we found our voice.

33:49.488 --> 33:51.949
Now I chill real ill
When I start to chill

33:52.032 --> 33:54.409
When I fill my pockets
With a knot of dollar bills

33:54.493 --> 33:56.995
Sipping pints of ale
Out the window sill

33:57.079 --> 33:59.540
When I get my fill I'm chilly chill

33:59.623 --> 34:02.417
Now I just got home
Because I'm out on bail

34:02.501 --> 34:05.337
What's the time?
It's time to buy ale

34:05.420 --> 34:09.007
So Russell and Rick put
"Hold It Now, Hit It" out on Def Jam.

34:09.091 --> 34:12.761
And then it starts getting played
on all these mix shows and in clubs,

34:12.844 --> 34:14.388
which is a big deal to us.

34:15.138 --> 34:20.310
Our song was getting played next to songs
like LL Cool J's "Rock the Bells,"

34:20.393 --> 34:23.730
Run-DMC's "Peter Piper,"
songs that we loved.

34:23.813 --> 34:25.190
We got this gig going to Philly.

34:25.274 --> 34:27.234
And we went on
and we just dropped the record.

34:27.317 --> 34:30.112
I remember we put "Hold It Now" on,
and the whole place just went crazy,

34:30.195 --> 34:31.446
like, the whole club.

34:31.530 --> 34:34.699
And that was a pretty amazing feeling.
I was like, "Damn."

34:34.783 --> 34:37.286
So, I'm 19 years old.

34:37.369 --> 34:39.246
I got a little money in my pocket.

34:39.329 --> 34:40.831
Rappers know who I am.

34:40.914 --> 34:42.583
We're getting into clubs for free.

34:42.666 --> 34:45.002
We're getting drink tickets.
We're talking to girls.

34:45.085 --> 34:46.295
-We're getting drunk.
-"Ad-Rock."

34:46.378 --> 34:48.547
We're fuckin' around.
We're writing lyrics on napkins.

34:48.630 --> 34:49.672
We're cracking each other up.

34:49.755 --> 34:53.217
And then we go to the studio
and make a song out of all that shit.

34:53.302 --> 34:54.719
Next night, next song.

34:54.803 --> 34:57.973
Four and three and two and one
What up!

34:58.056 --> 35:01.101
And when I'm on the mic the suckers run
Word!

35:01.185 --> 35:03.103
Down with Ad-Rock and Mike D
And you ain't

35:03.187 --> 35:05.564
And I got more juice
Than Picasso got paint

35:05.647 --> 35:08.150
Got rhymes that are rough
And rhymes that are slick

35:08.233 --> 35:10.694
I'm not surprised you're on my dick

35:10.777 --> 35:11.778
B-E-A-S-T-I-E...

35:11.862 --> 35:15.490
So we're recording all the time,
making songs.

35:15.574 --> 35:18.577
And Russell would just keep
putting them out as singles.

35:18.660 --> 35:21.121
-We put out "Paul Revere."
-Smash hit.

35:21.705 --> 35:23.916
We put out "The New Style," this song.

35:23.999 --> 35:25.167
Smash hit!

35:25.918 --> 35:30.255
And at a certain point, Russell came
into the studio and he was like,

35:30.339 --> 35:33.050
"You guys are the greatest rap group
of all time.

35:33.133 --> 35:35.344
You're gonna be making
a full-length album."

35:35.427 --> 35:39.181
So, while we're doing that, Adam and I,

35:39.264 --> 35:41.350
we're still living
at these shitty apartments.

35:41.433 --> 35:43.644
You know, like you do when
you're 19 years old.

35:43.727 --> 35:48.315
But Yauch moved into this
nice new apartment in Brooklyn Heights.

35:48.398 --> 35:50.108
Now, he lived there for free

35:50.192 --> 35:52.611
because he was
the superintendent of the building.

35:53.195 --> 35:54.696
-It's true.
-Yeah.

35:54.780 --> 35:58.116
So if your radiator broke,
Yauch would come up to fix it.

35:59.451 --> 36:01.370
I mean, he had zero qualifications
for the job,

36:01.453 --> 36:03.872
but he could do just about anything
on instinct.

36:03.956 --> 36:06.583
But late one night,
me and Mike stopped by the apartment,

36:06.667 --> 36:09.545
and he had this tape deck set up
on a table in the kitchen.

36:09.628 --> 36:10.963
But it wasn't a cassette deck.

36:11.046 --> 36:13.382
It was a quarter-inch
reel-to-reel tape deck,

36:13.465 --> 36:14.883
which I didn't even know he had.

36:14.967 --> 36:17.052
And I'm there and I'm studying this,

36:17.135 --> 36:20.138
trying to figure out
what this whole thing is.

36:20.222 --> 36:22.391
I mean, he's got the tape
from the one reel.

36:22.474 --> 36:25.811
And instead of just going to, like,
the other reel, like it usually would,

36:25.894 --> 36:29.106
it comes out the one reel,
it's going around a mic stand,

36:29.189 --> 36:31.567
and then it goes around another mic stand.

36:31.650 --> 36:33.527
And then it goes around a chair.

36:33.610 --> 36:35.112
And then back into the second reel.

36:35.195 --> 36:37.614
I mean, Adam and I
are looking at this thing and we're like,

36:37.698 --> 36:40.742
"This is like
a fucking magic trick, right?"

36:40.826 --> 36:43.662
And then Yauch gets up
and he presses play.

36:50.919 --> 36:52.462
So the intro drumbeat

36:52.546 --> 36:55.299
to Led Zeppelin's
"When the Levee Breaks" starts playing.

36:55.382 --> 36:59.261
But instead of the whole song playing,
it was just the intro beat over and over.

36:59.344 --> 37:02.347
I'd seen DJs do it
with two records and turntables.

37:02.431 --> 37:05.184
But I'd never seen it done
with reel-to-reel tape.

37:05.267 --> 37:08.562
The sound and the visual
were so magical to us.

37:08.645 --> 37:10.063
Yauch told us that he'd heard about

37:10.147 --> 37:13.358
Jimi Hendrix and Sly Stone
doing tape loops and he wanted to try it.

37:13.442 --> 37:15.152
Where did he hear about that?

37:15.235 --> 37:17.779
There was no YouTube or Google
back then, right?

37:18.363 --> 37:20.449
We took Yauch's creation to the studio,

37:20.532 --> 37:23.368
and we made a song called
"Rhymin' & Stealin'."

37:26.288 --> 37:29.333
Ali Baba and the forty thieves

37:29.416 --> 37:32.336
Ali Baba and the forty thieves

37:32.419 --> 37:35.631
Ali Baba and the forty thieves

37:35.714 --> 37:37.716
Torchin' and crackin'
And rhymin' and stealin'...

37:37.799 --> 37:41.220
So while we were writing and recording
what would become Licensed to Ill,

37:41.303 --> 37:45.516
Rick Rubin was also producing
Run-DMC's new album Raising Hell.

37:46.391 --> 37:49.937
Now, their version
of the Aerosmith song "Walk This Way"

37:50.020 --> 37:53.357
was a massive mainstream
radio and MTV hit, right?

37:53.440 --> 37:56.485
And Run-DMC fuckin' blew up
all over the world.

37:56.568 --> 37:58.445
They went on tour that summer in '86.

37:58.529 --> 38:00.113
Russell had us open for them.

38:00.197 --> 38:02.199
Beastie Boys' function
in the Raising Hell Tour

38:02.282 --> 38:04.368
is to get everybody pumped up
to check out the shows.

38:04.451 --> 38:06.286
So we figured
we'd raise a lot of hell on stage.

38:06.370 --> 38:08.956
And we'd just, sort of,
you know, get the audience going.

38:09.039 --> 38:12.543
They were so large
by the time their tour got to Miami,

38:12.626 --> 38:16.588
the promoters upgraded their venue
from basketball arena to baseball stadium.

38:18.048 --> 38:22.427
Joe Perry and Steven Tyler from Aerosmith
were flying down from Miami

38:22.511 --> 38:24.221
just to do the one song with them.

38:24.304 --> 38:26.682
And it was bound to be
a fuckin' spectacle.

38:27.641 --> 38:29.643
She starts swingin'
With the boys in tune

38:29.726 --> 38:31.562
And her feet just fly up in the air...

38:31.645 --> 38:37.192
Cut to the big moment, when Aerosmith
is about to hit the stage to join Run-DMC

38:37.276 --> 38:40.445
to play the number one song
on the entire planet.

38:40.529 --> 38:43.323
They walk out and the crowd goes wild.

38:43.407 --> 38:47.202
But now there's some other guy on stage.

38:47.286 --> 38:48.412
Yauch.

38:52.332 --> 38:54.918
Yauch happened to have a bass with him.

38:55.002 --> 38:58.046
And Jam Master Jay from Run-DMC
thought it'd be funny

38:58.130 --> 39:01.758
for him to play bass with them
and Aerosmith for the big song,

39:01.842 --> 39:05.971
on stage, in a baseball stadium, in Miami.

39:06.054 --> 39:09.349
And Yauch fucking delivered majestically.

39:09.433 --> 39:13.061
The look on the Aerosmith guys' faces
was fantastic bemusement.

39:13.145 --> 39:15.230
"Who's this dirty drunk guy on stage?

39:15.314 --> 39:18.275
And why is he playing bass with us?"

39:19.359 --> 39:20.736
Throughout the whole song,

39:20.819 --> 39:23.363
Yauch kept trying
to go back-to-back guitar-player style

39:23.447 --> 39:26.450
with fucking Joe Perry,
who was having none of it, right?

39:26.533 --> 39:27.534
And it's like--

39:27.618 --> 39:32.080
It ended up with Yauch chasing him
around the stage running backwards.

39:32.164 --> 39:35.792
And all of us were
on the side of the stage,

39:35.876 --> 39:40.464
watching, screaming,
laughing and loving it.

39:42.633 --> 39:46.178
And not only was it really fucking fun
being on tour

39:46.261 --> 39:48.180
and hanging out with Run-DMC,

39:48.263 --> 39:51.308
but we learned so much
watching them night after night.

39:51.391 --> 39:53.810
I mean, it was like
we were at rap finishing school.

39:53.894 --> 39:58.690
Yes, yes, y'all, we don't stop
Keep it on, shockin' the place

39:58.774 --> 39:59.775
Well...

40:01.109 --> 40:02.402
Got nothin' to prove

40:02.486 --> 40:05.072
Pay attention
My intention is to bust a move

40:05.155 --> 40:08.033
Drinkin' quarts and cans
And bottles and sixes

40:08.116 --> 40:11.119
Between the turntables
Keep the...

40:11.203 --> 40:13.580
My name's Run
I got the deuces wild

40:13.664 --> 40:16.333
Listen to the rhymes
I'm bustin' the style

40:16.416 --> 40:18.919
Name's DMC and he's by my side

40:19.002 --> 40:21.547
So take the mic...

40:21.630 --> 40:23.173
But when we got back home,

40:23.257 --> 40:27.302
we found out that Rick had gone
and mixed and finished our whole record.

40:27.386 --> 40:30.055
It was weird that he just went
and did it without us knowing.

40:30.764 --> 40:34.351
I mean, Yauch was always
into the technical aspects of recording,

40:34.434 --> 40:38.021
so I'm sure it must've bummed him out
or pissed him off.

40:38.105 --> 40:40.899
But what Rick did was pretty incredible.

40:40.983 --> 40:42.818
He took our weird rap songs

40:42.901 --> 40:47.447
and he made them sound clean, and big,
and polished, and ready for the radio.

40:47.531 --> 40:50.826
They are more like real anthems
and less like a joke.

40:55.247 --> 40:59.251
Brass Monkey, that funky Monkey

40:59.334 --> 41:03.213
Brass Monkey junkie
That funky Monkey

41:03.297 --> 41:04.798
Brass Monkey

41:05.549 --> 41:06.967
Chapter 4:

41:07.050 --> 41:10.596
"Earlier We Had Mentioned a Song
That We Thought Had Changed Everything.

41:10.679 --> 41:12.181
And It Had, In a Way.

41:12.264 --> 41:15.767
But This Is Actually the Song
That Changed Everything."

41:18.187 --> 41:23.066
So, fun fact, we were almost done
with our record Licensed to Ill,

41:23.150 --> 41:24.693
but Russell said it wasn't long enough

41:24.776 --> 41:27.029
and so we needed just,
like, one more song.

41:27.112 --> 41:30.574
And Yauch and his friend Tom Cushman
had a side band called Brooklyn.

41:30.657 --> 41:33.202
And they had this song called
"Fight for Your Right (To Party)."

41:33.285 --> 41:34.328
And Yauch was like,

41:34.411 --> 41:37.247
"Why don't we use that Brooklyn song
and use it for Beastie Boys?"

41:37.331 --> 41:38.498
They made that song as a joke.

41:38.582 --> 41:42.753
Like, a kind of fake anthem
making fun of party bros and frat guys.

41:42.836 --> 41:47.090
Now, we had never actually met
a party bro or a frat guy.

41:47.633 --> 41:50.052
But we thought that shit
was hilarious to make fun of.

41:50.135 --> 41:53.597
So our big idea was
to take a little bit of this.

41:55.057 --> 41:56.350
A little bit of that.

41:57.976 --> 41:59.645
A little bit of this.

42:01.146 --> 42:04.483
And then about half a cup of that.

42:04.566 --> 42:07.778
And then you mix
all these things together.

42:07.861 --> 42:09.363
And what you get is...

42:09.446 --> 42:13.951
You gotta fight for your right

42:14.034 --> 42:16.537
To party

42:17.829 --> 42:20.040
Shit starts happening really fast.

42:20.123 --> 42:23.001
I mean, it felt like the next day,
our record comes out.

42:23.085 --> 42:24.920
Then the video comes out.

42:25.003 --> 42:26.046
It's everywhere.

42:26.129 --> 42:28.841
I mean, I'm just at home
eating my Fruity Pebbles.

42:28.924 --> 42:32.636
And I'm watching it play, like,
five times an hour on MTV.

42:32.719 --> 42:34.388
Everybody watched MTV back then.

42:34.471 --> 42:36.849
And we were on that shit constantly.

42:36.932 --> 42:40.769
Our homemade video that we made
at our friend's apartment is now playing

42:40.853 --> 42:44.982
in between fuckin' Michael Jackson,
Prince and Tina Turner videos.

42:45.065 --> 42:48.527
I mean, that was some crazy shit.

42:49.111 --> 42:51.530
So, we went from being famous in--

42:51.613 --> 42:53.907
-Crazy shit.
-Come on.

42:56.785 --> 42:59.997
We went from being famous in,
like, a 14-block radius

43:00.080 --> 43:02.583
to being known
in the underground hip-hop scene

43:02.666 --> 43:06.879
to being recognized walking down
the street after Licensed to Ill came out.

43:06.962 --> 43:10.382
I mean, everywhere I went
people would start yelling like...

43:10.465 --> 43:12.342
"Yo, Mike D."

43:12.426 --> 43:14.136
"What's up, homeboy?"

43:14.219 --> 43:16.430
Same thing with me and Yauch.
We'd be walking down the street,

43:16.513 --> 43:18.557
someone might recognize us,
and they'd be like...

43:18.640 --> 43:20.434
"Yo, Mike D."

43:23.103 --> 43:24.229
True story.

43:24.313 --> 43:27.149
So, we were really feeling ourselves.

43:27.232 --> 43:29.026
And about two months later,

43:29.109 --> 43:33.572
Russell sends us out on our first
big headlining tour of America.

43:33.655 --> 43:34.656
So what did we do?

43:34.740 --> 43:37.701
We brought Dave Scilken
and Cey and DJ Hurricane

43:37.784 --> 43:39.203
and all our other friends with us.

43:39.286 --> 43:41.580
Our record was selling like crazy.

43:41.663 --> 43:43.999
And that's when things started
to feel really different.

43:44.082 --> 43:46.126
Being famous in our city was one thing.

43:46.210 --> 43:48.545
But being famous in a mall
in Missoula, Montana

43:48.629 --> 43:50.839
is something else entirely.

43:50.923 --> 43:52.591
So before the tour started,

43:52.674 --> 43:54.676
Russell Simmons had us meet
with some weird dude

43:54.760 --> 43:57.387
to talk about what we wanted on stage.

43:57.471 --> 44:01.892
So just to fuck with this guy,
we were like, "Yeah, homes, you know,

44:01.975 --> 44:07.064
we want a fuckin' ten-foot
six-pack of Budweiser for a DJ riser."

44:07.147 --> 44:09.274
-"Check."
-"We want a fuckin' go-go dancer cage."

44:09.358 --> 44:10.651
-"Check."
-"We want this big box

44:10.734 --> 44:13.529
with a 25-foot dick coming out of it
at the end of the show, right?"

44:13.612 --> 44:15.113
-"That's easy. Yeah. No problem."
-Right?

44:15.197 --> 44:16.615
And the next thing you know,

44:16.698 --> 44:20.035
we get to Missoula, Montana
for the first show, and there it is.

44:29.586 --> 44:32.297
Mike D, wop it up, wop it up, wop it up.

44:32.840 --> 44:35.843
We were wopping it up.
We were pretty excited.

44:36.718 --> 44:40.430
Now, we had no idea who was gonna show up
to see us play.

44:41.265 --> 44:44.393
We definitely didn't think
that the party bro frat dudes

44:44.476 --> 44:46.270
that we were making fun of
were gonna come.

44:46.353 --> 44:50.566
But turns out that they loved
"Fight for Your Right (To Party)."

44:50.649 --> 44:53.026
And you know what? We liked being loved.

44:53.110 --> 44:56.947
So fuck it.
Pass me a 40. Let's get fucked up.

44:58.907 --> 45:03.537
Now, everything that Russell had said
would happen was actually happening.

45:03.620 --> 45:07.916
He'd show up all the time in some random
city on tour and remind us. He'd be like,

45:08.000 --> 45:10.002
"See, I told you motherfuckers.

45:10.085 --> 45:12.546
Y'all gonna be bigger than Cap'n Crunch."

45:13.755 --> 45:15.757
The shows kept getting bigger and bigger.

45:15.841 --> 45:18.594
A thousand people one night,
2,000 the next.

45:18.677 --> 45:21.221
-Chicago, Atlanta--
-Miami.

45:21.305 --> 45:22.514
Miami.

45:23.140 --> 45:24.141
-Munich.
-Munich.

45:24.224 --> 45:25.225
Houston.

45:25.309 --> 45:28.145
Shows, hotels,
after-parties, after-after-parties.

45:28.228 --> 45:34.193
Now we were having the fucking times
of our lives, and shit was blowing up.

