chants and throwing shit at us.

50:03.045 --> 50:05.839
And then it turned into
a full-on hailstorm of beer can--

50:05.923 --> 50:07.674
Jesus Christ, Mike. Come on.

50:08.258 --> 50:11.178
A full-on hailstorm
of beer cans and bottles.

50:11.678 --> 50:15.516
So mid-show, we broke the fuck out,
and we drove back to London.

50:16.433 --> 50:19.353
After all this, you think we would've
taken a break for a sec, right?

50:19.436 --> 50:21.438
You know, just to let things
calm down a little.

50:21.522 --> 50:22.523
But we didn't.

50:22.606 --> 50:26.235
We went straight from all of that
to tour Japan.

50:26.318 --> 50:27.694
Then after the tour of Japan,

50:27.778 --> 50:31.323
we came back to the United States
and toured that shit all over again.

50:31.406 --> 50:32.574
No breaks.

50:33.742 --> 50:34.910
We just didn't stop.

50:35.661 --> 50:37.704
Russell was like,
"You're going back on tour.

50:37.788 --> 50:40.999
You're gonna make a lot of money.
And you're gonna be happy rock stars."

50:41.083 --> 50:43.210
"All right, Russell. Whatever you say."

50:46.255 --> 50:47.673
I mean, he was the manager.

50:47.756 --> 50:51.635
If he's like, "You're going out on tour,"
well, then that's what you do.

50:52.719 --> 50:54.429
We didn't really question it so much.

50:54.513 --> 50:57.599
We felt like we had to be
out there doing this.

50:57.683 --> 51:00.477
But we weren't really mature enough
to be able to express

51:00.561 --> 51:03.105
that we started to not like our own songs.

51:03.730 --> 51:05.524
Which is a really shitty feeling.

51:06.567 --> 51:10.070
Yauch was the first one to start
showing signs of not wanting to be there.

51:10.988 --> 51:13.448
I mean, it's not like we weren't having
fun as friends.

51:13.991 --> 51:16.326
It's just, the show started
to become just that.

51:16.410 --> 51:17.411
A show.

51:17.995 --> 51:19.121
A fucking gimmick.

51:20.372 --> 51:21.832
I mean, we were all tired.

51:22.749 --> 51:24.126
We missed our families.

51:24.668 --> 51:25.919
We missed being home.

51:26.837 --> 51:29.798
We missed things like
just going to the deli to get a sandwich.

51:30.465 --> 51:32.801
We missed being the people we used to be.

51:33.510 --> 51:36.597
All the dumb shit we were saying
and the go-go cage

51:36.680 --> 51:39.516
and the fucking beer
and the dick in the box...

51:39.600 --> 51:41.977
the whole thing was just
getting fucking embarrassing.

51:43.061 --> 51:45.230
We were burning out.

51:45.314 --> 51:48.233
In a flash,
Beastie Boys went from being

51:48.317 --> 51:51.069
the funny, tipsy guy
with the lampshade on his head

51:51.153 --> 51:55.157
to the ugly drunk dude that people
were trying to get out of their apartment.

51:55.240 --> 51:57.993
It's like that Bill Murray movie
Groundhog Day.

51:58.535 --> 52:01.788
You know, where he keeps living
the same day over and over.

52:02.623 --> 52:05.083
But in our movie, it was the fucking dick

52:05.167 --> 52:08.587
going up in the air
at the end of every show.

52:10.172 --> 52:15.260
The problem was, we built the fucking box,
and we're the dicks stuck inside the box.

52:16.178 --> 52:19.389
It became, "How can we
get through the show fast enough

52:19.473 --> 52:25.395
so the stupid dick can get back in the box
and we can get the fuck off stage."

52:38.158 --> 52:39.618
What ever happened to the Beastie Boys?

52:39.701 --> 52:42.162
In late 1986,
they released Licensed to Ill,

52:42.246 --> 52:44.623
one of the most successful
debut albums of all time.

52:44.706 --> 52:47.459
But they've yet to record a follow-up
and have gone their separate ways

52:47.543 --> 52:50.295
since their tour with Run-DMC
ended last fall.

52:50.379 --> 52:53.507
These days, Mike D and MCA
are playing in bands around New York.

52:53.590 --> 52:56.802
As for Ad-Rock, he's been in Los Angeles
making his movie debut.

53:09.231 --> 53:11.400
You just transferred
to Sherman, didn't you?

53:12.609 --> 53:14.945
