53:58.030 --> 54:02.367
spun me barfing all around the world,
and dropped me on my head in Hollywood.

54:02.951 --> 54:05.245
And that's when I got cast
to do that movie.

54:05.829 --> 54:09.583
I was 22 years old, and I did not know
what the fuck had just happened.

54:10.417 --> 54:12.961
I hadn't talked to Adam or Mike
for a couple months.

54:13.045 --> 54:14.713
We didn't have a fight
or a falling out or anything,

54:14.796 --> 54:18.425
but it was, like, the first time we didn't
really wanna hang out with each other.

54:18.509 --> 54:22.179
I guess we just needed a break
to go our separate ways for a minute.

54:23.013 --> 54:26.517
Yauch was in New York, and he was
really into his other band, Brooklyn.

54:27.643 --> 54:29.978
And I was in LA doing that movie.

54:30.646 --> 54:32.147
And Mike was...

54:33.023 --> 54:34.233
Mike, what were you doing?

54:34.316 --> 54:39.071
Honestly, I was just
experimenting with a lot of drugs.

54:39.488 --> 54:40.489
Right, right.

54:43.784 --> 54:48.372
So as for me,
I was running from all kinds of things.

54:48.455 --> 54:51.708
My mom had just passed away,
right before Licensed to Ill came out.

54:51.792 --> 54:54.378
And the chance to escape
into becoming a different person

54:54.461 --> 54:56.839
couldn't have come
at the more perfect time.

54:57.673 --> 55:01.426
So after the tour, I continued to run away
from anything I was feeling.

55:03.053 --> 55:05.848
One day after filming,
I got back to the hotel I was staying at,

55:05.931 --> 55:07.182
and someone at the front desk said

55:07.266 --> 55:09.351
that there was a package
waiting for me in my room.

55:09.852 --> 55:13.355
I get in my room and there's this
huge box, and it's from Yauch.

55:14.022 --> 55:17.359
I open the box,
and inside the box is another box.

55:17.442 --> 55:20.070
And then another box,
and another box, and another box.

55:21.280 --> 55:24.992
And then there was this big ziplock bag
with coffee grounds in it.

55:25.617 --> 55:28.829
So inside of that mess
was a cassette tape.

55:30.372 --> 55:33.041
It was the demos for his band Brooklyn.

55:33.750 --> 55:37.254
It's weird to go from talking to someone
every single day for years

55:37.337 --> 55:39.965
to all of a sudden not hear from them
for a couple months.

55:40.048 --> 55:42.801
So it was really cool
that he sent me this tape of his music.

55:43.302 --> 55:46.138
Like, he did it
so we could be connected as friends.

55:46.930 --> 55:48.891
But it definitely made me pause for a sec.

55:48.974 --> 55:50.976
Like, maybe that's just
what he's doing now.

55:51.059 --> 55:53.812
Maybe he's done with Beastie Boys,
and we're not a band anymore.

55:54.313 --> 55:59.193
Well, turns out we kind of weren't a band,
because Yauch quit.

55:59.276 --> 56:02.613
I mean, he didn't tell us about it
until a couple years later.

56:03.113 --> 56:05.616
He was sick of being
the drunk guy at the party.

56:05.699 --> 56:08.118
Yauch said that Russell
wasn't trying to hear him

56:08.202 --> 56:10.662
and he kept trying to convince him
that it was all fine

56:10.746 --> 56:12.372
and that he should just get back on tour

56:12.456 --> 56:15.250
and put water in a beer can
and splash it all around

56:15.334 --> 56:17.544
and a whole bunch of other clown stuff.

56:17.628 --> 56:19.046
That was enough for Yauch.

56:19.129 --> 56:21.673
So he told Russell, "I quit."

56:21.757 --> 56:26.053
So during all this madness,
we stopped being paid royalties.

56:26.720 --> 56:28.305
We made money for playing shows,

56:28.388 --> 56:31.016
like, big shows, like,
Madison Square Garden shows.

56:31.099 --> 56:36.104
But zero dollars for the multiplatinum
smash hit Licensed to Ill.

56:36.188 --> 56:38.941
The fucking record
that a group of friends made together,

56:39.024 --> 56:41.860
had intense and real fun making together,

56:41.944 --> 56:43.779
spent hours and hours laughing

56:43.862 --> 56:48.659
at coffee shops and clubs and studios,
dorm rooms, taxis, and parties...

56:48.742 --> 56:51.078
But now, for whatever reason,

56:51.161 --> 56:55.123
the record label decides
that they should not fucking pay us.

56:55.666 --> 56:58.585
Rick and Russell. Our friends. Def Jam.

56:59.169 --> 57:01.088
We'd been there with them
from the beginning.

57:01.630 --> 57:05.342
We felt that Def Jam's success
was success for us and vice versa.

57:05.425 --> 57:07.010
'Cause we were all friends.

57:07.094 --> 57:09.763
Allegedly, Russell said
that we were in breach of our contract

57:09.847 --> 57:13.058
because we hadn't started recording
a new record for Def Jam yet.

57:13.517 --> 57:17.104
I mean, Russell wanted a "Fight for
Your Right (To Party) Part 2" now.

57:17.187 --> 57:18.188
When Russell signed us,

57:18.272 --> 57:22.067
we thought that he believed in us
in some bigger way.

57:22.150 --> 57:26.488
But in hindsight, he just needed three
white rappers to get on MTV.

57:26.572 --> 57:28.365
I mean, we could've been anybody.

57:29.908 --> 57:32.244
Anyways, back to me. Los Angeles.

57:33.495 --> 57:35.664
