58:15.037 --> 58:16.788
I don't know, you guys.
It's pretty fucking hot.

58:16.872 --> 58:18.373
I don't know what else to say.

58:20.167 --> 58:22.336
Anyways, I was out in Hollywood.

58:22.419 --> 58:24.087
All right, all right, all right.

58:26.924 --> 58:30.886
So, I'm out in Hollywood, and I was
at this big Hollywood party, right?

58:30.969 --> 58:33.972
And I'm hanging out by the pool,
as you do at Hollywood parties.

58:34.640 --> 58:38.310
And so I hear this awesome music
playing from somewhere.

58:41.438 --> 58:44.858
"What is that?" So I'm trying to
figure out where this music's coming from,

58:44.942 --> 58:47.444
so I'm walking around the party
trying to figure it out, right?

58:47.528 --> 58:49.196
-Champagne, sir?
-Thank you, Mike D.

58:50.072 --> 58:52.533
This is how I walk
when I walk through Hollywood parties.

58:53.450 --> 58:54.785
Donnie Wahlberg? Hey. What's up?

58:54.868 --> 58:55.994
Are you done with that?

58:56.787 --> 59:00.707
So, I'm following the sound to try
to figure out where it's coming from,

59:00.791 --> 59:02.376
and I get to a cassette player.

59:02.960 --> 59:05.379
And at the cassette player
is this guy Matt Dike

59:05.462 --> 59:07.172
and these guys the Dust Brothers.

59:08.715 --> 59:10.592
And they said that they'd made this music.

59:10.676 --> 59:14.346
It was so awesome that I called Adam
and Mike the next day, and I was like,

59:14.429 --> 59:17.766
"You guys should come out to Los Angeles,
and we should meet with these guys."

59:17.850 --> 59:18.934
And they came out.

59:19.017 --> 59:21.311
Now, I didn't know what it was
gonna be like when they came out,

59:21.395 --> 59:24.439
because we hadn't seen each
other for a few months.

59:24.523 --> 59:27.943
But when they got there,
it felt like how it was supposed to be.

59:28.026 --> 59:30.195
We hung out, we listened to this music.

59:30.696 --> 59:33.824
So, like, any of this other stuff
we were doing was fine, right?

59:33.907 --> 59:38.370
Yauch's band Brooklyn,
me in the movie, Mike being Mike.

59:40.163 --> 59:41.999
But it reminded me

59:42.082 --> 59:44.960
the Beastie Boys is what we should
be doing with our lives, right?

59:45.043 --> 59:46.128
For me.

59:49.590 --> 59:52.217
And we made a very conscious
decision moving forward.

59:52.801 --> 59:57.681
No manager, no producer,
no record label would call the shots.

59:57.764 --> 59:59.766
It would be just the three of us.

01:00:04.771 --> 01:00:05.647
So...

01:00:06.982 --> 01:00:11.445
There's not that many times in your life
when you realize you're in a new chapter.

01:00:11.528 --> 01:00:13.947
Chapter 6: "A New Chapter."

01:00:17.117 --> 01:00:20.954
The music the Dust Brothers was making
was incredible

01:00:21.038 --> 01:00:24.333
and totally inspired us
to want to make another record.

01:00:24.416 --> 01:00:27.503
But the reality is,
to continue being a band,

01:00:27.586 --> 01:00:30.130
we had to meet with
some new record labels.

01:00:30.214 --> 01:00:31.882
One of them was Capitol Records.

01:00:31.965 --> 01:00:35.344
So we go up to meet the big-time
president guy and he was like,

01:00:35.427 --> 01:00:38.639
"You guys didn't do anything
on Licensed to Ill. Let's be real.

01:00:38.722 --> 01:00:40.474
Rick and Russell did all that shit.

01:00:40.557 --> 01:00:42.351
You're, like, their creation."

01:00:42.434 --> 01:00:46.146
But the same time,
they're willing to bet on us,

01:00:46.230 --> 01:00:49.942
even though it's a long shot,
that we just might give them

01:00:50.025 --> 01:00:52.611
a "Fight for Your Right
(To Party) Part 2."

01:00:52.694 --> 01:00:55.072
Now, we're embarrassed about that song,

01:00:55.155 --> 01:00:59.535
but we're not so embarrassed
that we won't use it to get a record deal.

01:01:01.787 --> 01:01:04.998
Right? So we get the record deal,
but now we need a manager.

01:01:05.082 --> 01:01:09.086
And so we pick a manager
for maybe not the smartest reasons ever.

01:01:09.419 --> 01:01:13.298
We picked this guy because he managed
Kenny Rogers and Lionel Richie.

01:01:13.382 --> 01:01:15.133
And we thought that shit was funny.

01:01:15.926 --> 01:01:19.471
Sometimes dumb jokes aren't always

01:01:19.555 --> 01:01:22.516
the best things to guide
your financial future.

01:01:22.599 --> 01:01:23.934
All right?

01:01:24.017 --> 01:01:26.436
Also, we had this big idea.

01:01:26.520 --> 01:01:29.481
Like, okay, if we all live
in a house together,

01:01:29.565 --> 01:01:32.025
we're really gonna get
