So we took all this money
from our new fat record contract

01:01:36.780 --> 01:01:42.369
and we rented a super-expensive
fancy house up in the Hollywood Hills.

01:01:43.787 --> 01:01:46.081
But not just any house
in the Hollywood Hills.

01:01:46.164 --> 01:01:49.418
This house was like a '70s museum.

01:01:49.501 --> 01:01:53.505
It was like Hart to Hart combined with
The Love Boat combined with, like,

01:01:53.589 --> 01:01:55.591
the Regal Beagle from Three's Company.

01:01:56.675 --> 01:01:59.261
My man, Hart to Hart
was just a great callout right there.

01:01:59.344 --> 01:02:00.345
That was awesome.

01:02:01.096 --> 01:02:05.350
Anyway, this house was owned
by Alex and Madilyn Grasshoff.

01:02:05.434 --> 01:02:06.727
-Exactly.
-Small detail.

01:02:06.810 --> 01:02:09.271
Now, inside of this house
there's a locked closet.

01:02:09.354 --> 01:02:12.232
And so, you know,
when you're, like, in your 20s

01:02:12.316 --> 01:02:16.612
and you're curious and super high,
and there's a locked closet,

01:02:17.237 --> 01:02:18.405
what do you do?

01:02:18.488 --> 01:02:20.199
You fucking kick that closet open, right?

01:02:20.282 --> 01:02:21.491
You wanna know what's inside.

01:02:21.575 --> 01:02:25.537
Inside the closet
is all of Madilyn Grasshoff's

01:02:25.621 --> 01:02:29.333
awesome ensembles from the '70s.

01:02:29.416 --> 01:02:30.751
I mean...

01:02:30.834 --> 01:02:32.544
Yeah. Yeah.

01:02:32.628 --> 01:02:37.216
Like, we're talking suede
patchwork duster coats.

01:02:37.299 --> 01:02:39.384
I mean, like, fucking satin jumpsuits.

01:02:39.468 --> 01:02:42.721
Everything transplendent and wonderful.

01:02:42.804 --> 01:02:46.266
Like fur hats. I mean, special vests.

01:02:46.350 --> 01:02:48.435
You guys, would you
rather go have breakfast,

01:02:48.519 --> 01:02:51.146
you know, like,
in your Oscar Madison clothes?

01:02:51.230 --> 01:02:53.857
Or would you rather
go have breakfast like this?

01:02:56.527 --> 01:02:58.820
This is the house
that we stayed in, right? That's Mike.

01:02:58.904 --> 01:03:00.113
You look wonderful.

01:03:00.197 --> 01:03:01.406
Thank you, Adam.

01:03:01.490 --> 01:03:05.619
If you have a swimming pool and you don't
have a bridge over it, you're fucking up.

01:03:06.119 --> 01:03:08.038
But listen.
So my room wasn't in the house.

01:03:08.121 --> 01:03:10.832
It was, like, this weird side room
that was, like, over here.

01:03:10.916 --> 01:03:13.126
And in the swimming pool
was this little window

01:03:13.210 --> 01:03:16.839
that looked right into my room
and from the room into the pool.

01:03:16.922 --> 01:03:19.049
And every couple days,
at 6:00 in the morning,

01:03:19.132 --> 01:03:20.801
I'd hear this loud banging noise,

01:03:20.884 --> 01:03:22.928
and I'd wake up and see this.

01:03:25.430 --> 01:03:27.641
It was Yauch saying,
"Let's go get breakfast."

01:03:28.892 --> 01:03:32.688
So our daily routine was to wake up
at this crazy Grasshoff house,

01:03:32.771 --> 01:03:33.981
go have some breakfast,

01:03:34.064 --> 01:03:36.859
and then we'd go meet Matt Dike
and the Dust Brothers at the studio.

01:03:40.070 --> 01:03:41.363
Matt Dike was a DJ,

01:03:41.446 --> 01:03:45.200
and he had thousands and thousands
of records piled all over his apartment.

01:03:45.284 --> 01:03:47.119
And he was just cool.

01:03:47.202 --> 01:03:49.705
I don't know.
We wanted to know what he knew about.

01:03:49.788 --> 01:03:53.041
The Dust Brothers were computer science
students at Claremont College.

01:03:54.084 --> 01:03:55.335
EZ Mike was a DJ.

01:03:56.336 --> 01:03:58.046
John was, like, this computer wiz.

01:03:58.672 --> 01:04:02.301
And shit, we'd never even seen
a computer in a recording studio before.

01:04:02.926 --> 01:04:05.012
And we went sample crazy.

01:04:06.054 --> 01:04:07.055
It's the joint

01:04:15.439 --> 01:04:18.984
The Dust Brothers opened up
a whole new creative world for us.

01:04:19.067 --> 01:04:22.446
We were just layering
and layering and layering,

01:04:22.529 --> 01:04:26.241
making each song as dense as possible
with lyrics and samples and jokes.

01:04:26.325 --> 01:04:28.285
We're taking two things, three things.

01:04:28.368 --> 01:04:31.205
We're blending them in and out
so the song is like a whole collage.

01:04:31.288 --> 01:04:34.625
We thought we were
on some next-level shit.

01:04:34.708 --> 01:04:36.960
So like a pimp I'm pimpin'
I got a boat to eat shrimp in

01:04:37.044 --> 01:04:39.254
Nothing wrong with my leg
Just B-boy limpin'

01:04:39.338 --> 01:04:41.423
Got arrested at the Mardi Gras
For jumping on a float

01:04:41.507 --> 01:04:44.176
My man MCA's
Got a beard like a billy goat

01:04:44.259 --> 01:04:46.261
Ooh, ooh, is my disco call

01:04:46.345 --> 01:04:48.889
MCA, I'm gettin' rope y'all

01:04:52.684 --> 01:04:53.810
Now...

01:04:57.981 --> 01:05:01.026
I remember one night,
up at the Grasshoff house,

01:05:01.109 --> 01:05:05.280
Yauch was playing mixes of what
we were working on super, super loud.

01:05:05.364 --> 01:05:09.201
And we were looking out all over
the twinkling lights of Los Angeles below,

01:05:09.284 --> 01:05:12.120
and, well, we were
pretty stoned at the time.

01:05:12.204 --> 01:05:17.251
And Yauch turns to me and he goes,
"Yo, this is dope."

01:05:17.334 --> 01:05:22.089
And I elegantly replied,
"Yeah, this is pretty special, dude."

01:05:23.924 --> 01:05:25.259
I mean, it was, actually.

01:05:25.342 --> 01:05:29.346
I mean, because around this time,
Yauch got loose creatively.

01:05:29.429 --> 01:05:34.142
Now, without Rick and Russell around,
we were doing everything ourselves.

01:05:34.226 --> 01:05:37.688
See, a band's got a lot more to do
than just write a song and put it out.

01:05:37.771 --> 01:05:39.523
Like photo shoots,
press photos or whatnot.

01:05:39.606 --> 01:05:41.191
Like, after Licensed to Ill came out,

01:05:41.275 --> 01:05:43.610
the last thing we wanted to do
was some weird photo session

01:05:43.694 --> 01:05:45.445
with some stranger we didn't know.

01:05:45.529 --> 01:05:48.323
So Yauch had this idea. He's telling us,
"We'll do the pictures ourselves.

01:05:48.407 --> 01:05:51.451
You take this little, like, squeezy thing
and you connect to the camera,

01:05:51.535 --> 01:05:52.578
then we take our"--

01:05:52.661 --> 01:05:54.788
This here, right?

01:05:54.872 --> 01:05:56.039
I love that picture of you, Mike.

01:05:56.748 --> 01:05:57.958
Thank you.

01:05:58.041 --> 01:06:00.794
So then we had to make a record cover.
Of course, Yauch's like,

01:06:00.878 --> 01:06:06.675
"Simple. We're gonna use this camera
that takes a 360-degree picture

01:06:06.758 --> 01:06:08.510
and that's gonna be the album cover."

01:06:08.594 --> 01:06:12.097
Okay, here's the thing.
We're together every single day, always.

01:06:12.181 --> 01:06:17.060
So, like, Yauch would just know about
all these things and we're always like,

01:06:17.144 --> 01:06:18.145
"That's cool."

01:06:18.228 --> 01:06:20.731
"How the fuck does he know about that?
That's just so weird."

01:06:21.732 --> 01:06:23.817
Again, usually when you put out a record,

01:06:23.901 --> 01:06:29.031
the fancy record company
assigns you to a big-time fancy director.

01:06:29.114 --> 01:06:32.075
But, of course with us, like,
we were pretty paranoid at the time.

01:06:32.159 --> 01:06:34.411
We didn't trust anybody,
so Yauch was like,

01:06:34.494 --> 01:06:35.871
"No, no, we're gonna get my uncle,

01:06:35.954 --> 01:06:38.874
the legendary Swiss filmmaker
Nathaniel Hrnblowr.

01:06:38.957 --> 01:06:40.876
He's gonna come over,
he's gonna help us out,

01:06:40.959 --> 01:06:43.462
and he's gonna direct all of our videos."

01:06:44.671 --> 01:06:47.424
Yauch's humble about this, right?
Like, he credited his uncle

01:06:47.508 --> 01:06:50.511
for a lot of the experimentation
and for the direction.

01:06:50.594 --> 01:06:52.471
But, like, Yauch was the driving force.

01:06:54.306 --> 01:06:56.642
Actually, in the
"Looking Down the Barrel of a Gun" video,

01:06:56.725 --> 01:06:59.561
that stuff is just really us
wearing Madilyn Grasshoff's clothes.

01:06:59.645 --> 01:07:02.022
That was one day that we just
put on a bunch of her clothes

01:07:02.105 --> 01:07:04.358
and just went and drove around
and videotaped ourselves.

01:07:04.441 --> 01:07:07.027
So thanks, Madilyn, for the solid.

01:07:07.945 --> 01:07:10.280
Steal from the rich
And I'm out robbing banks

01:07:10.364 --> 01:07:12.449
Give it to the poor
And I always give thanks

01:07:12.533 --> 01:07:15.285
Because I got more stories
Than J.D.'s got Salinger

01:07:15.369 --> 01:07:17.538
-I hold the title
-And you are the challenger

01:07:17.621 --> 01:07:19.665
Hrnblowr was around a lot at the time,

01:07:19.748 --> 01:07:22.543
which was kinda cool
'cause he was Yauch's uncle,

01:07:22.626 --> 01:07:25.796
but like, he was a fucking drunk, Mike.
I don't know how else to say it.

01:07:25.879 --> 01:07:27.172
He liked his wineskin, yeah.

01:07:27.256 --> 01:07:29.049
So we're all doing our thing
and then there's, like,

01:07:29.132 --> 01:07:32.636
this weird old Swiss guy
just crashed out on the couch.

01:07:32.719 --> 01:07:36.181
Look. This is what we used to
have to deal with, with Yauch's uncle.

01:07:36.265 --> 01:07:38.308
Yeah, this is a little strange for me,

01:07:38.392 --> 01:07:41.937
because I'm not used to
being on this side of the camera.

01:07:42.020 --> 01:07:45.566
I'm preferred to be behind it.

01:07:47.526 --> 01:07:49.152
You're certainly dressed for the part.

01:07:49.236 --> 01:07:52.406
This is our traditional clothing
from where I'm from.

01:07:52.489 --> 01:07:54.449
And you may joke about it,

01:07:54.533 --> 01:07:59.246
but I may joke about you walking
around in a business suit someplace,

01:07:59.329 --> 01:08:01.415
and maybe that's silly to me, okay?

01:08:01.498 --> 01:08:03.417
Maybe I'm laughing at you right now.

01:08:05.919 --> 01:08:10.007
Somehow, between the weed,
the breakfast, the parties,

01:08:10.090 --> 01:08:13.594
we finish the record
and the artwork and we hand it all in.

01:08:17.430 --> 01:08:18.432
Like this.

01:08:18.515 --> 01:08:20.850
So, we were excited.

01:08:20.934 --> 01:08:23.312
We finished this record
we were really proud of.

01:08:23.395 --> 01:08:25.397
People were gonna buy it and hear it

01:08:25.479 --> 01:08:27.357
and see that we were more than just those

01:08:27.441 --> 01:08:29.318
"Fight for Your Right (To Party)"
guys, right?

01:08:29.401 --> 01:08:32.237
You think we would've been humbled
by the falling out with Def Jam.

01:08:32.321 --> 01:08:33.529
-No.
-But no.

01:08:33.613 --> 01:08:34.781
We were on top of the world.

01:08:34.865 --> 01:08:37.618
Yo, what's up?
It's the Beastie Boys for Yo! MTV Raps.

01:08:37.701 --> 01:08:38.577
Boy!

01:08:38.660 --> 01:08:40.787
Girl, you know it's true

01:08:41.580 --> 01:08:45.082
Mike D is in love with you

01:08:45.167 --> 01:08:46.710
In the lead-up to the record release,

01:08:46.792 --> 01:08:47.961
we were doing loads of interviews.

01:08:48.045 --> 01:08:50.255
I mean, shit, we were ready
to play Madison Square Garden

01:08:50.339 --> 01:08:51.965
and blow the fuck up.

01:08:53.591 --> 01:08:55.844
And Capitol Records were all in.

01:08:55.928 --> 01:08:57.679
They were maybe even
more amped than we were.

01:08:57.763 --> 01:08:59.055
The Beasties are not

01:09:00.557 --> 01:09:02.643
concept masterminded by someone else.

01:09:03.644 --> 01:09:07.189
And the extraordinary success of their
first album, Licensed to Ill,

01:09:07.272 --> 01:09:08.273
was no fluke.

01:09:09.858 --> 01:09:11.902
Word on the street from respected rappers,

01:09:11.984 --> 01:09:15.572
from Eazy-E to MC Hammer to Public Enemy,

01:09:15.656 --> 01:09:17.866
is that these guys are real indeed.

01:09:17.950 --> 01:09:19.618
The music is stupid fresh.

01:09:20.786 --> 01:09:21.995
They have the stuff.

01:09:22.955 --> 01:09:24.162
So enough talk.

01:09:24.872 --> 01:09:26.917
Let's raise the flag up the pole.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:28.210
Batman, watch out.

01:09:28.877 --> 01:09:31.587
The Beasties are gonna be
in your face this summer.

01:09:32.214 --> 01:09:36.844
And then, on July 25th, 1989...

01:09:36.926 --> 01:09:39.220
With the entire world waiting...

01:09:39.888 --> 01:09:43.934
Our new record,
Paul's Boutique, comes out, and...

01:09:47.479 --> 01:09:48.479
nothing.

01:09:50.107 --> 01:09:51.108
Crickets.

01:09:53.109 --> 01:09:55.612
Chapter 7: "Crickets."

01:09:57.155 --> 01:10:00.868
No radio was playing the new songs.
No MTVs playing the new video.

01:10:00.951 --> 01:10:02.911
No shows. Nobody gave a shit.

01:10:02.995 --> 01:10:04.121
They all moved on.

01:10:04.788 --> 01:10:07.082
It felt like we were a haircut
that they got in the seventh grade

01:10:07.165 --> 01:10:09.585
and thought was really cool,
but now they were embarrassed about it

01:10:09.668 --> 01:10:11.712
and just wanted to pretend
it never happened.

01:10:11.795 --> 01:10:13.714
I remember being really surprised

01:10:13.797 --> 01:10:17.384
that Paul's Boutique didn't do better
than it did when it came out,

01:10:17.467 --> 01:10:20.470
because I kept feeling
while we were working on it

01:10:20.554 --> 01:10:22.931
like it was so much better of a record
than Licensed to Ill.

01:10:23.015 --> 01:10:25.142
When we were working on
Paul's Boutique, I just kept thinking,

01:10:25.225 --> 01:10:26.476
"Wow, this sounds so much better.

01:10:26.560 --> 01:10:29.229
I would imagine this is gonna do,
like, much better than that."

01:10:29.313 --> 01:10:33.108
So when it didn't, then I was kinda like,
"Well, you never know."

01:10:33.192 --> 01:10:35.402
So now I don't even
try and guess these days.

01:10:35.485 --> 01:10:38.572
Nobody cared that we had a new record out.

01:10:39.114 --> 01:10:45.204
No one, that is, except for
our dear old friend Mr. Don Cornelius.

01:10:45.287 --> 01:10:47.372
Beasties, Beasties.

01:10:48.040 --> 01:10:48.999
How you doing, gentlemen?

01:10:49.082 --> 01:10:50.417
-What's up, Don?
-All right.

01:10:50.501 --> 01:10:51.710
-Hi.
-Hey, Don.

01:10:51.793 --> 01:10:53.378
-Yo, what's up, man?
-What's up?

01:10:54.338 --> 01:10:55.964
-What's up, Don?
-All right.

01:10:56.048 --> 01:10:57.508
-Yeah. Okay.
-Peace.

01:10:57.591 --> 01:10:59.092
To you too, brother.

01:10:59.176 --> 01:11:01.303
Hey, man, what is "the Don Cornelius"?

01:11:01.386 --> 01:11:03.847
-Don Cornelius.
-You made it up, man.

01:11:03.931 --> 01:11:05.724
-You're the man.
-Don Cornelius.

01:11:05.807 --> 01:11:09.770
Yo, but seriously, we just wanna say
we've been on the show before, whatever,

01:11:09.853 --> 01:11:12.189
but we've been watching this show since--

01:11:12.272 --> 01:11:15.317
You know, a lot of people don't realize,
since whatever, since we were kids.

01:11:15.400 --> 01:11:16.527
That's how long.

01:11:16.610 --> 01:11:19.029
You know,
I got the Soul Train albums here.

01:11:19.112 --> 01:11:21.114
Whenever you're in town,

01:11:21.198 --> 01:11:23.575
you know, always make this a stop, okay?

01:11:23.659 --> 01:11:24.660
-All right, man.
-All right.

01:11:24.743 --> 01:11:27.079
The Beastie Boys!

01:11:29.540 --> 01:11:32.209
You threatened Don Cornelius.
You got right in his--

01:11:32.292 --> 01:11:33.293
Can we show that again?

01:11:33.377 --> 01:11:36.296
You know,
I got the Soul Train albums here.

01:11:36.839 --> 01:11:38.131
Why, Mike?

01:11:38.423 --> 01:11:41.969
I'm wearing, like,
some kind of blouse, dude, okay?

01:11:42.052 --> 01:11:44.429
It looks like you don't even know
how to wear a shirt.

01:11:45.973 --> 01:11:49.351
We look like four different people
in four different bands.

01:11:49.810 --> 01:11:52.104
Now, I just want to point out, Adam,

01:11:52.187 --> 01:11:53.605
not to go in too hard,

01:11:53.689 --> 01:11:58.569
but it looks like you're about to throw up
on DJ Hurricane's shoulder right there.

01:11:58.652 --> 01:12:00.112
You're not doing too good.

01:12:00.195 --> 01:12:02.447
I think I was either
about to fall asleep or cry.

01:12:03.615 --> 01:12:08.120
And I have to apologize right now
to Mr. Don Cornelius,

01:12:08.203 --> 01:12:13.709
because obviously I'm being
very unnecessarily aggressive towards him.

01:12:14.251 --> 01:12:17.754
I guess whatever I smoked is, like,
the stuff that makes you, like--

01:12:17.838 --> 01:12:21.383
I don't know, look at your best friend
and just, like, punch him in the gut

01:12:21.466 --> 01:12:23.051
and then knee him in the nuts.

01:12:25.304 --> 01:12:26.597
Like the mad, aggressive strain.

01:12:26.680 --> 01:12:29.725
Christ, Mike.
It's very-- It's very specific.

01:12:29.808 --> 01:12:33.312
I think the one I smoked,
it must have been called Steven Seagal.

01:12:36.106 --> 01:12:37.524
You guys.

01:12:37.608 --> 01:12:42.738
Footnote: In, like, 1988,
we went to see Jimmy Cliff play.

01:12:43.363 --> 01:12:46.116
And we're super stoned
in the back of the thing,

01:12:46.200 --> 01:12:47.743
and in the middle of
the Jimmy Cliff show--

01:12:47.826 --> 01:12:51.830
It's like summertime, outdoor show.
Stops the song, and he's like, "Right now,

01:12:51.914 --> 01:12:55.584
I wanna bring out to the stage
a great, great actor.

01:12:55.667 --> 01:12:57.169
Mr. Steven Seagal."

01:12:57.252 --> 01:12:58.420
He was a little more like,

01:12:58.504 --> 01:13:01.673
"Right now, great, great actor!"

01:13:02.007 --> 01:13:03.425
You had to do the Jamaican accent.

01:13:03.759 --> 01:13:06.887
And fucking Steven Seagal comes out,
in like a full ninja outfit,

01:13:06.970 --> 01:13:09.264
and starts banging on the timbales
and then leaves.

01:13:09.348 --> 01:13:10.974
Yup. And you know what, Adam?

01:13:11.058 --> 01:13:13.101
That was some crazy shit.

01:13:13.185 --> 01:13:14.561
Cra-Cra-Cra--

01:13:17.481 --> 01:13:18.815
Crazy shit.

01:13:19.983 --> 01:13:21.944
Crazy shit.

01:13:22.027 --> 01:13:22.903
Crazy shit.

01:13:24.404 --> 01:13:27.324
Is that just not funny?
I don't know what-- It's not funny.

01:13:27.407 --> 01:13:28.784
I think we were right to cut it.

01:13:28.867 --> 01:13:30.494
Yeah, yeah. I think so. We'll cut it.

01:13:31.828 --> 01:13:35.374
All right. So we clearly were a mess
right at this point, right?

01:13:35.457 --> 01:13:36.667
Definitely.

01:13:36.750 --> 01:13:41.255
So putting all your efforts, your time,
your excitement into something

01:13:41.338 --> 01:13:42.756
and hearing crickets...

01:13:43.298 --> 01:13:44.716
I was a little crushed.

01:13:45.133 --> 01:13:48.011
I mean, we're all ready
to have Paul's Boutique blow up.

01:13:48.262 --> 01:13:51.056
And it came and went,
and it was kind of sobering.

01:13:56.520 --> 01:13:58.814
Yo, what's up? Mike D here, what's up?

01:13:59.773 --> 01:14:00.899
Oh, hello, my friend.

01:14:00.983 --> 01:14:03.443
It's Bill Harper, your accountant.

01:14:03.527 --> 01:14:05.362
Oh, shit. What's up, homes?
How you feeling?

01:14:05.445 --> 01:14:07.489
I need to discuss some things with you.

01:14:07.573 --> 01:14:10.325
As it turns out,
your financial picture has changed a bit.

01:14:10.409 --> 01:14:13.120
Seems you guys
don't really have any money anymore.

01:14:13.203 --> 01:14:14.288
What?

01:14:14.371 --> 01:14:17.875
You see, my friend Mike D,
you guys went to LA, you moved there,

01:14:17.958 --> 01:14:21.503
you rent this crazy house with
a fucking bridge over a swimming pool,

01:14:21.587 --> 01:14:23.422
you get these crazy expensive cars,

01:14:23.505 --> 01:14:26.425
you spend millions of dollars
at crazy-expensive studios.

01:14:26.508 --> 01:14:27.509
That was for work though.

01:14:27.593 --> 01:14:31.555
You spend fucking $4,200
on fucking almond milk a week.

01:14:31.638 --> 01:14:32.639
Also for work.

01:14:32.723 --> 01:14:36.185
And you know what happens?
You go fucking broke.

01:14:36.268 --> 01:14:38.478
Shit, Bill. That sucks.

01:14:38.854 --> 01:14:39.897
Yeah, it does.

01:14:40.397 --> 01:14:41.356
Hey, I gotta go, Mike.

01:14:41.440 --> 01:14:43.650
I got Donny Osmond on the other line.

01:14:46.570 --> 01:14:49.698
Now we call this time period
Paul's Purgatory.

01:14:51.575 --> 01:14:53.744
But the good news is

01:14:53.827 --> 01:14:56.455
we signed a multi-record deal
with Capitol,

01:14:56.538 --> 01:14:58.498
so whether they liked it or not,

01:14:58.582 --> 01:15:02.419
they had to give us the money
to make another record.

01:15:02.836 --> 01:15:05.672
But we had to downsize a little bit.

01:15:05.839 --> 01:15:07.841
We had wasted all this money

01:15:07.925 --> 01:15:11.011
recording Paul's Boutique
at these fancy studios.

01:15:11.094 --> 01:15:12.721
So we figured, "Fuck it.

01:15:12.804 --> 01:15:15.933
Let's take the money for the record,
build our own studio,

01:15:16.016 --> 01:15:17.601
and we'd save a whole lot."

01:15:17.976 --> 01:15:21.271
We found this old Elks Lodge ballroom
in Atwater,

01:15:21.355 --> 01:15:23.357
this sleepy part of Los Angeles,

01:15:23.440 --> 01:15:25.776
where nothing was happening, right?

01:15:25.859 --> 01:15:29.071
We built a bare-bones recording studio
with a basketball hoop

01:15:29.154 --> 01:15:31.073
and Yauch made a skate ramp.

01:15:31.156 --> 01:15:34.076
We wanted to start playing
more and more of our own music again,

01:15:34.159 --> 01:15:36.578
even if we didn't know
what that meant at first.

01:15:36.912 --> 01:15:38.497
So we moved out of that Grasshoff house.

01:15:38.580 --> 01:15:40.832
We each got much cheaper places to live.

01:15:40.916 --> 01:15:44.378
I mean, shit, Yauch was living
in a fucking log cabin.

01:15:44.628 --> 01:15:45.754
Right? For real.

01:15:45.838 --> 01:15:47.714
We definitely downsized.

01:15:48.465 --> 01:15:51.927
But like always, we wanted to do
what we always do:

01:15:52.386 --> 01:15:54.805
Just make music, hang out, bullshit.

01:15:55.180 --> 01:15:57.266
But this time
we wanted to do it differently.

01:15:57.766 --> 01:16:00.102
We figured instead of just sampling
music that we love,

01:16:00.185 --> 01:16:02.312
why not try playing it
with our instruments?

01:16:02.396 --> 01:16:05.607
I mean, shit, why not try to sound
like The Meters?

01:16:07.484 --> 01:16:09.069
We sucked at first.

01:16:09.152 --> 01:16:11.947
I was a punk guitar player.
Now I'm trying to play jazz and soul.

01:16:12.030 --> 01:16:13.532
It wasn't pretty.

01:16:14.074 --> 01:16:16.493
-I mean, Mike was decent on the drums.
-Thank you.

01:16:16.577 --> 01:16:18.996
But Yauch goes and buys an acoustic bass

01:16:19.079 --> 01:16:20.873
and just magically knew how to play it.

01:16:21.582 --> 01:16:24.501
Like-- I don't know if you've ever tried
to play one of those things,

01:16:24.585 --> 01:16:25.919
but it's really fucking hard.

01:16:26.003 --> 01:16:30.132
So our new routine was to show up
at our clubhouse every day

01:16:30.215 --> 01:16:34.136
and play music with our friends
Money Mark and Mario C.

01:16:34.428 --> 01:16:37.097
We met Mario C.
working on Paul's Boutique.

01:16:37.347 --> 01:16:39.099
He was the Dust Brothers' engineer,

01:16:39.183 --> 01:16:41.476
and we asked him
to help us build our studio.

01:16:41.560 --> 01:16:44.938
And we ended up getting him to stay
and make music with us.

01:16:45.105 --> 01:16:48.108
Now, when we were staying at
that crazy expensive house in Hollywood,

01:16:48.192 --> 01:16:50.485
Mike crashed his car
into the driveway gate.

01:16:50.569 --> 01:16:51.612
True.

01:16:51.695 --> 01:16:54.573
But Mario had a friend
who was a carpenter, Mark Nishita,

01:16:54.656 --> 01:16:55.782
and he came over to fix it.

01:16:55.866 --> 01:16:59.328
But Mario said he's also
this really great keyboard player.

01:16:59.411 --> 01:17:01.830
So when we got our studio
and started playing,

01:17:01.914 --> 01:17:05.667
we asked him to come help us
make our sound more funky.

01:17:05.751 --> 01:17:06.835
Turn that up a little bit.

01:17:11.798 --> 01:17:14.384
So that's Yauch on the bass.
I'm on the guitar.

01:17:14.468 --> 01:17:17.596
Listen to that guitar, Adam.
Your guitar break.

01:17:17.679 --> 01:17:19.848
You got some high-hat patterns, Mike.

01:17:21.225 --> 01:17:24.311
Mark's on the organ. I mean,
we're getting it together, right, Mike?

01:17:30.734 --> 01:17:33.529
So this went on for a year or so,
and we couldn't have been happier.

01:17:34.321 --> 01:17:37.157
We're learning how to play our instruments
and we're chopping up samples.

01:17:37.241 --> 01:17:38.825
We're making beats we were into.

01:17:38.909 --> 01:17:41.286
We were making music
we really liked.

01:17:42.037 --> 01:17:45.249
The only problem was
we weren't finishing any songs.

01:17:46.416 --> 01:17:48.794
When it came time
to do vocals on a song,

01:17:48.877 --> 01:17:50.712
we'd get hesitant and shy.

01:17:50.796 --> 01:17:52.047
We'd been in a weird headspace,

01:17:52.130 --> 01:17:55.008
just kind of confused with
what our voices were.

01:17:55.092 --> 01:17:57.052
What should our vocals even sound like?

01:17:57.511 --> 01:18:00.597
We think we're rappers, because
our first two albums were rap albums.

01:18:00.848 --> 01:18:03.475
But what were we gonna rap about?

01:18:03.559 --> 01:18:04.935
We didn't feel like we're the guys

01:18:05.018 --> 01:18:07.729
who made
Licensed to Ill or Paul's Boutique.

01:18:07.938 --> 01:18:10.649
But we didn't know exactly
where that left us.

01:18:13.527 --> 01:18:15.487
And then one morning I was at home

01:18:15.571 --> 01:18:18.615
and I got woken up by the kind of call
I never got before.

01:18:19.700 --> 01:18:22.035
A call from a friend's parent,
crying on the phone.

01:18:23.579 --> 01:18:25.289
Our friend Dave Scilken's dad called

01:18:25.372 --> 01:18:27.291
and told me that Dave had died
of an overdose.

01:18:27.666 --> 01:18:29.084
He was 20 years old.

01:18:30.919 --> 01:18:33.172
I hadn't really lost
a close friend like that.

01:18:34.381 --> 01:18:37.509
People on our periphery,
but no one that close.

01:18:38.010 --> 01:18:39.636
This felt really different.

01:18:39.720 --> 01:18:41.221
David Scilken.

01:18:42.389 --> 01:18:44.975
We all went back to New York
for Dave's service.

01:18:45.058 --> 01:18:46.643
-Say hi, Dave.
-Hi.

01:18:47.186 --> 01:18:48.437
It was just so fucking sad.

01:18:48.520 --> 01:18:50.898
Yo, this is Dave Scilken.
This is Shadi One.

01:18:51.815 --> 01:18:54.109
Afterwards, we all ended up at some bar,

01:18:54.193 --> 01:18:56.653
'cause that's just what you do
when a friend passes away.

01:18:56.737 --> 01:19:00.240
You get beers and sit around
and tell stories about them.

01:19:01.658 --> 01:19:03.243
Now we felt a little self-conscious

01:19:03.327 --> 01:19:04.995
when we ran into old friends at that time.

01:19:05.704 --> 01:19:08.624
We thought when they'd see us, they'd see
the "Fight for Your Right (To Party)" guys

01:19:08.707 --> 01:19:10.209
and would be jerks about it.

01:19:10.667 --> 01:19:12.836
But it wasn't like that with Kate
and all our old friends.

01:19:12.920 --> 01:19:15.422
We just sat around
and missed our friend Dave.

01:19:15.506 --> 01:19:18.467
And it meant a lot more to the three of us
than we realized.

01:19:19.009 --> 01:19:21.303
There was a reason
that we'd all been friends.

01:19:22.012 --> 01:19:24.723
And the whole trip was like a connection
to New York City.

01:19:26.350 --> 01:19:28.519
And it felt good
to be with everybody again.

01:19:28.602 --> 01:19:33.065
Kills himself and

01:19:33.148 --> 01:19:38.612
How do I make friends now

01:19:39.321 --> 01:19:40.739
As sad as this all was,

01:19:40.822 --> 01:19:43.075
we went back to our clubhouse in LA.

01:19:43.534 --> 01:19:45.702
And I don't know if it was
meeting up with our friends

01:19:45.786 --> 01:19:49.039
or having our lives switched up,
but we got inspired.

01:19:49.122 --> 01:19:51.708
And all of a sudden,
we started finishing shit.

01:19:55.921 --> 01:19:58.006
And it gave us this sense of, like,

01:19:58.090 --> 01:19:59.675
just keep doing what you're doing.

01:19:59.967 --> 01:20:02.177
Our music could include
everything we loved,

01:20:02.261 --> 01:20:05.347
and our album could be like a mixtape
of all different types of music,

01:20:05.430 --> 01:20:08.058
including any sounds
or dialogue or samples

01:20:08.141 --> 01:20:09.685
or anything that we thought was funny.

01:20:10.143 --> 01:20:13.438
When you're 22, you don't know
what to do with your feelings.

01:20:13.522 --> 01:20:16.483
We couldn't articulate it to each other
how we felt.

01:20:16.567 --> 01:20:18.902
But I do think that
having all of those feelings

01:20:18.986 --> 01:20:20.654
and not knowing what to do with them,

01:20:20.737 --> 01:20:23.198
you kind of just put it
into whatever you're making.

01:20:23.574 --> 01:20:25.951
People, how you doin'
There's a new day dawnin'

01:20:26.034 --> 01:20:28.370
For the earth mother
It's a brand new mornin'

01:20:28.453 --> 01:20:30.789
For such a long while
There's been such a longin'

01:20:30.873 --> 01:20:33.250
But now the sun is shinin'
Let's roll back the awnin'

01:20:38.297 --> 01:20:40.716
This is a type of kinda
Like a formal dedication

01:20:40.799 --> 01:20:43.093
Givin' out a shout
For much inspiration

01:20:43.177 --> 01:20:45.262
All I ever really want to do
Is get nice

01:20:45.345 --> 01:20:47.723
Get loose
And goof a little slice of life

01:20:48.140 --> 01:20:50.434
Sendin' out love
To all corners of the land

01:20:50.517 --> 01:20:52.561
I jump up on the stage
And take the mic in my hand

01:20:52.644 --> 01:20:55.355
I'm not playin' the role
Just bein' who I am

01:20:55.439 --> 01:20:57.691
And if you try to dis me
I couldn't give a damn

01:20:59.276 --> 01:21:01.987
Yo, we were like, "Fuck it," right?

01:21:03.739 --> 01:21:04.948
I mean--

01:21:05.908 --> 01:21:07.326
We should make whatever we like.

01:21:07.409 --> 01:21:10.621
I mean, if The Clash have punk and reggae
and rap songs on their records,

01:21:10.704 --> 01:21:11.830
why can't we?

01:21:11.914 --> 01:21:14.833
I mean, why not a stoner song
next to a rap song

01:21:14.917 --> 01:21:16.627
next to a hardcore song?

01:21:25.093 --> 01:21:26.970
This is our song "Time for Livin'."

01:21:27.346 --> 01:21:31.225
We just wanted to experiment and do all
different types of shit that we could do.

01:21:31.433 --> 01:21:33.644
We played our instruments
and we sampled that.

01:21:33.727 --> 01:21:35.229
We'd never done that before.

01:21:35.312 --> 01:21:39.733
And while experimenting, we gave ourselves
permission to do stuff like sing.

01:21:41.485 --> 01:21:43.111
We'd never done that either.

01:21:43.195 --> 01:21:45.572
But we were like, "Fuck it. Let's try it."

01:21:45.656 --> 01:21:49.701
There's something
Coming to the surface

01:21:51.662 --> 01:21:54.206
There's fire all around

01:21:55.374 --> 01:21:57.960
But this is all illusion

01:21:58.043 --> 01:22:00.170
This song's called
"Something's Got to Give."

01:22:00.254 --> 01:22:03.090
Yauch wrote the lyrics,
which are about change and growth.

01:22:03.173 --> 01:22:07.094
And that makes sense, because right around
this time, Yauch was exploring everything.

01:22:07.469 --> 01:22:10.180
There was no boundary
he wasn't interested in crossing.

01:22:10.973 --> 01:22:13.642
Like calling me at fucking
4:30 in the morning, being like,

01:22:13.725 --> 01:22:15.477
"I'm recording these pigeons.
You gotta hear 'em."

01:22:15.561 --> 01:22:16.979
I'm like, "Dude, I'm sleeping."

01:22:17.646 --> 01:22:19.106
That's not what we're talking about.

01:22:20.315 --> 01:22:22.442
I'm saying he was
in full-on transformation mode.

01:22:22.901 --> 01:22:24.152
He was traveling the world,

01:22:24.236 --> 01:22:27.197
he was snowboarding out of helicopters,
he was trekking in Nepal.

01:22:28.198 --> 01:22:30.659
Whatever it was, he went out
and found out about it.

01:22:31.285 --> 01:22:33.996
Film, Buddhism, music,

01:22:34.663 --> 01:22:37.249
meeting people everywhere
from all different worlds.

01:22:38.208 --> 01:22:41.545
If you can feel what I'm feeling
Then it's a musical masterpiece...

01:22:44.089 --> 01:22:46.842
What's running through my mind
Comes through in my walk

01:22:46.925 --> 01:22:49.553
True feelings are shown
From the way that I talk...

01:22:49.636 --> 01:22:53.557
So after two full years
of being immersed in our clubhouse,

01:22:54.266 --> 01:22:56.435
we finished our record Check Your Head.

01:22:59.396 --> 01:23:02.858
Chapter 8: "The Record
That Changed Everything."

01:23:04.860 --> 01:23:07.112
We were really psyched on Check Your Head,

01:23:07.446 --> 01:23:11.867
and we wanted to go out and play shows,
so we found a new manager, John Silva.

01:23:12.951 --> 01:23:16.413
Now, he told us that if we were serious
about going on tour,

01:23:16.496 --> 01:23:19.499
we'd have to bust our asses
playing tons of clubs

01:23:19.583 --> 01:23:23.921
and work super hard to try and build it
back up to playing bigger places.

01:23:24.379 --> 01:23:25.672
He was honest with us.

01:23:25.756 --> 01:23:30.302
And he was right, 'cause not that many
people gave a shit about us at the time.

01:23:30.385 --> 01:23:32.054
And he's still our manager today.

01:23:32.387 --> 01:23:33.222
So...

01:23:35.140 --> 01:23:39.186
Good news-- Good news,
we now had our squad to go on tour.

01:23:40.062 --> 01:23:43.273
Bad news, we had to do a ton of work.

01:23:48.362 --> 01:23:50.614
Tumble outta bed
And I stumble to the kitchen

01:23:50.697 --> 01:23:52.699
Pour myself a cup of ambition

01:23:52.783 --> 01:23:55.702
And yawn and stretch
And try to come to life

01:23:57.746 --> 01:24:00.165
Jump in the shower
And the blood starts pumpin'

01:24:00.249 --> 01:24:02.209
Out on the street
The traffic starts jumpin'

01:24:02.292 --> 01:24:06.380
With folks like me on the job
From 9 to 5

01:24:06.463 --> 01:24:11.176
Workin' 9 to 5
What a way to make a livin'

01:24:11.260 --> 01:24:15.889
Barely gettin' by
It's all takin' and no givin'

01:24:15.973 --> 01:24:20.352
They just use your mind
And they never give you credit

01:24:20.435 --> 01:24:25.232
It's enough to drive you
Crazy if you let it...

01:24:25.983 --> 01:24:29.361
So five years earlier,
we're at Madison Square Garden, right?

01:24:29.444 --> 01:24:31.738
-Oh, yeah.
-And now we're playing clubs.

01:24:31.989 --> 01:24:36.201
You'd think we'd be bummed out about it,
but actually, falling off can be fun.

01:24:36.827 --> 01:24:39.371
Even though we're playing
to just a couple hundred people,

01:24:39.746 --> 01:24:40.831
those shows were packed.

01:24:41.456 --> 01:24:44.251
The crowd was way different now
than it was in '87.

01:24:44.668 --> 01:24:46.962
Licensed to Ill was, like, arena rock.

01:24:47.045 --> 01:24:51.300
The shows in '92 were packed
with like-minded weirdos.

01:24:51.383 --> 01:24:52.843
People we felt connected to.

01:24:53.218 --> 01:24:55.220
I mean, we were playing shows for people

01:24:55.304 --> 01:24:56.930
we would actually wanna hang out with.

01:24:57.306 --> 01:25:00.559
But we were still figuring out
how to be this new version of our band,

01:25:00.976 --> 01:25:04.813
and after a year of playing shows,
we started to know what we were doing.

01:25:04.897 --> 01:25:07.774
It wasn't until, like, the end
of the Check Your Head tour

01:25:07.858 --> 01:25:12.070
that I actually and confidently
considered myself to be a musician.

01:25:18.118 --> 01:25:22.497
So we'd just spent a year touring
and we started recording again.

01:25:22.581 --> 01:25:26.001
We were having so much fun being together
and playing music together,

01:25:26.084 --> 01:25:27.085
why stop?

01:25:27.419 --> 01:25:31.423
It was almost like Check Your Head
and Ill Communication were one thing,

01:25:31.507 --> 01:25:33.634
and we just kept going and going.

01:25:34.218 --> 01:25:37.179
I mean, we were psyched
to go into the studio every night.

01:25:37.513 --> 01:25:40.307
All of our friends would come through,
and they'd hang out.

01:25:40.390 --> 01:25:43.685
I mean, shit,
we had a basketball court and a half-pipe.

01:25:43.769 --> 01:25:45.896
I mean, not to mention tons of music gear.

01:25:46.772 --> 01:25:48.941
So many amazing people would stop by.

01:25:49.233 --> 01:25:54.821
Q-Tip played basketball, and he recorded
a verse on a song, "Get It Together."

01:25:55.447 --> 01:25:58.617
Christian Hosoi and Jason Lee,
they'd come over to skate.

01:25:59.034 --> 01:26:00.786
Biz Markie would come over a lot.

01:26:01.203 --> 01:26:03.705
Now one day our old friend Jill Cunniff

01:26:03.789 --> 01:26:07.543
called me and asked to listen to the demo
tape of her band Luscious Jackson.

01:26:07.960 --> 01:26:08.877
Yauch--

01:26:10.963 --> 01:26:11.964
Yauch was like,

01:26:12.047 --> 01:26:15.259
"This is awesome. We should just
start a record label and put it out."

01:26:15.342 --> 01:26:17.427
Now we have a record label, Grand Royal.

01:26:17.511 --> 01:26:21.223
The music was amazing,
and what made it even more special to us,

01:26:21.640 --> 01:26:25.018
Kate joined Luscious Jackson
when they went out to play shows.

01:26:25.519 --> 01:26:28.605
So ten years later
we're back in each other's lives.

01:26:32.150 --> 01:26:35.779
So all this stuff was happening
under one roof, G-Son, our studio.

01:26:36.238 --> 01:26:38.323
Now one day I walked in,

01:26:38.407 --> 01:26:41.076
and I heard Yauch playing
this awesome bass line.

01:26:41.159 --> 01:26:44.538
It was so good, it seemed like
it must've been a song already.

01:26:44.621 --> 01:26:47.124
I was like, "Yo, Yauch. What is that?"

01:26:47.958 --> 01:26:50.377
And he was like,
"It's ours. I just wrote it."

01:26:50.752 --> 01:26:53.422
So I sat down.
I start playing drums with him.

01:27:00.637 --> 01:27:04.141
Then Keyboard Money Mark sits down.
He starts playing the organ.

01:27:04.224 --> 01:27:07.227
And then Adam puts on his guitar.
He starts to play.

01:27:07.311 --> 01:27:09.688
We made a quick arrangement
and we recorded it.

01:27:10.105 --> 01:27:12.065
It was the fastest song we'd ever made,

01:27:12.441 --> 01:27:14.818
and it was kind of
our favorite instrumental we had.

01:27:14.902 --> 01:27:16.445
But for whatever reason,
it just sat around

01:27:16.528 --> 01:27:18.447
for months and months with no vocals.

01:27:19.031 --> 01:27:20.657
When we were getting ready
to finish the record,

01:27:20.741 --> 01:27:23.076
we knew we had to
do something with that song.

01:27:23.660 --> 01:27:25.746
We tried a bunch of different ideas
to make it a rap song,

01:27:25.829 --> 01:27:26.872
but it wasn't working.

01:27:26.955 --> 01:27:30.417
And I had this idea
that I would go to Mario C.'s house

01:27:30.501 --> 01:27:33.504
and he would record me
screaming a bunch of stuff.

01:27:33.587 --> 01:27:36.840
The lyrics were all about
how Mario was the worst person ever

01:27:36.924 --> 01:27:39.968
and how he was always
sabotaging us and holding us back.

01:27:40.052 --> 01:27:41.845
I thought it would be funny
to stand next to him

01:27:41.929 --> 01:27:43.514
and scream that shit when he recorded it.

01:27:44.056 --> 01:27:47.935
So, so, so, so listen up
'Cause you can't say nothin'

01:27:48.393 --> 01:27:50.562
You'll shut me down
With a push of your button

01:27:50.646 --> 01:27:51.605
But, yo, I'm...

01:27:51.688 --> 01:27:53.774
I had this idea that we should
take some pictures of us

01:27:53.857 --> 01:27:56.193
as undercover cops
eating donuts and shit, right?

01:27:56.610 --> 01:28:00.989
But we were like, "Fuck it.
We should make a video for that instead."

01:28:01.490 --> 01:28:04.201
And Spike came over, and we
played dress-up, like we usually do.

01:28:04.284 --> 01:28:05.827
Just running around like maniacs

01:28:05.911 --> 01:28:09.164
with no proper permits or cops
or fire department or anything.

01:28:09.414 --> 01:28:11.750
'Cause what you see
You might not get

01:28:12.125 --> 01:28:14.962
And we can bet
So don't you get souped yet...

01:28:15.045 --> 01:28:17.756
Scheming on a thing, that's a mirage

01:28:17.840 --> 01:28:20.717
I'm trying to tell you now
It's sabotage

01:28:29.893 --> 01:28:33.188
Well, that changed
everything for us again.

01:28:33.730 --> 01:28:37.067
That summer, we begin headlining
the Lollapalooza tour.

01:28:38.443 --> 01:28:40.571
So, we're in Minnesota.

01:28:40.654 --> 01:28:44.825
We're in this huge field and there's,
like, bonfires off in the distance,

01:28:44.908 --> 01:28:46.702
and people are going crazy.

01:28:46.785 --> 01:28:50.455
And we go back on for our encore,
and we play "Sabotage."

01:28:50.539 --> 01:28:53.959
And a sea of people go next-level crazy.

01:28:54.042 --> 01:28:57.379
We come off the stage,
and we look at each other, and we're like,

01:28:57.462 --> 01:28:59.840
"Wow. We have our new last song."

01:29:02.342 --> 01:29:06.597
And to think all of that came from Yauch
just playing a bass line.

01:29:12.728 --> 01:29:16.356
Now, all of us have been in a room
where a friend of yours, you know,

01:29:16.440 --> 01:29:19.443
just kinda says or does something
randomly that seems cool.

01:29:20.194 --> 01:29:23.113
But when one of those things
that doesn't seem like much in the moment

01:29:23.197 --> 01:29:25.741
becomes something
long-lasting and impactful...

01:29:26.909 --> 01:29:28.785
well, that just doesn't happen that often.

01:29:29.119 --> 01:29:31.663
Now, last year
we did a bunch of interviews

01:29:31.747 --> 01:29:33.665
about Beastie Boys Book that we wrote.

01:29:34.041 --> 01:29:35.751
And the thing
that we were most asked about

01:29:35.834 --> 01:29:39.004
were these lyrics that Yauch
had written for a song, "Sure Shot."

01:29:39.296 --> 01:29:41.924
I want to say a little something
That's long overdue

01:29:42.007 --> 01:29:44.134
The disrespect to women
Has got to be through

01:29:44.218 --> 01:29:46.720
To all the mothers and the sisters
And the wives and friends

01:29:46.803 --> 01:29:49.306
I want to offer my love
And respect to the end

01:29:55.646 --> 01:29:59.483
Now, when he said that, it wasn't, like,
some huge, momentous occasion.

01:29:59.566 --> 01:30:02.903
It was just something
that Yauch wrote with some other lyrics

01:30:02.986 --> 01:30:05.155
and said it
when it was his turn on the mic.

01:30:05.572 --> 01:30:08.575
And we were, like,
"Wow. That's cool that he said that."

01:30:09.159 --> 01:30:13.622
Not only did he speak to a lot of people,
he spoke to the two of us.

01:30:14.790 --> 01:30:19.086
So those years recording and touring on
those two records were so important to us.

01:30:19.419 --> 01:30:21.129
We changed directions of our band.

01:30:21.505 --> 01:30:24.299
We changed how we wanted to be
as people and friends.

01:30:24.716 --> 01:30:27.386
We thought about the world
instead of just our world.

01:30:28.512 --> 01:30:30.472
When we were large in 1987,

01:30:30.556 --> 01:30:34.643
we were on American Bandstand
and we did not give a fuck.

01:30:34.726 --> 01:30:38.188
You wake up late for school
Man, you don't wanna go

01:30:41.900 --> 01:30:44.987
We weren't really, like,
working on our craft so much.

01:30:46.947 --> 01:30:51.577
But seven years later, when we played
"Sabotage" at the MTV awards,

01:30:51.827 --> 01:30:53.453
we were locked in.

01:31:33.702 --> 01:31:38.123
Yo, when we would play festivals
or TV shows with other bands on it,

01:31:38.207 --> 01:31:40.375
we looked at that shit like a competition.

01:31:40.459 --> 01:31:41.835
We played to win.

01:31:42.336 --> 01:31:43.879
We said that kinda half joking,

01:31:43.962 --> 01:31:46.965
but, like, kinda half
almost for 100% serious, right?

01:31:47.716 --> 01:31:51.386
I mean, we wanted everyone that watched
that show or went to that festival

01:31:51.470 --> 01:31:53.388
to go home
and tell their friends the next day,

01:31:53.472 --> 01:31:56.225
"Fucking Beastie Boys
housed the set," right?

01:31:56.308 --> 01:31:57.893
We played that shit to win.

01:31:59.269 --> 01:32:03.482
So when we played those MTV awards,
I mean, we won. Yeah, Mike? No?

01:32:03.565 --> 01:32:04.399
-Yes? No?
-Definitely.

01:32:04.483 --> 01:32:05.484
Got the "W," yes?

01:32:05.567 --> 01:32:07.903
No doubt. Pulled down the "W," people.

01:32:08.445 --> 01:32:12.282
But... later that night,
Spike Jonze was nominated

01:32:12.366 --> 01:32:16.078
for best director
for the "Sabotage" video, but didn't win.

01:32:18.455 --> 01:32:22.042
And that's when Yauch's Uncle Hrnblowr
fucking lost it.

01:32:23.585 --> 01:32:26.630
The winner
of best director in a video is...

01:32:30.008 --> 01:32:30.926
Go ahead.

01:32:31.260 --> 01:32:32.261
R.E.M.

01:32:42.563 --> 01:32:48.193
This is an outrage, because
Spike is the director that has just--

01:32:48.277 --> 01:32:51.822
I'm from Switzerland, okay?
Let me just tell everyone that. And--

01:32:53.031 --> 01:32:58.287
And since I was a small boy,
I had dream that Spike would win this.

01:32:59.121 --> 01:33:00.622
And now this has happened,

01:33:00.706 --> 01:33:03.208
and I just wanna tell everyone
that this is a farce.

01:33:03.584 --> 01:33:07.588
That I had all the ideas
for Star Wars and everything.

01:33:13.510 --> 01:33:14.761
Wow.

01:33:18.557 --> 01:33:23.437
Chapter 9:
"I'm Going Back to New York City."

01:33:23.520 --> 01:33:26.565
I do believe I've had enough

01:33:28.233 --> 01:33:30.652
So Los Angeles was great for us, right?

01:33:30.736 --> 01:33:33.071
From having houses
with bridges over swimming pools,

01:33:33.530 --> 01:33:36.950
a great studio, making great friends,
making tons of music,

01:33:37.534 --> 01:33:39.661
and actually becoming musicians.

01:33:39.745 --> 01:33:42.247
But we were there for eight years,
and time kinda flew by.

01:33:42.873 --> 01:33:45.417
We were around 30 years old by now,
and we missed home.

01:33:45.501 --> 01:33:47.044
I mean, we missed our families.

01:33:47.127 --> 01:33:49.338
Yauch was the first
to move back to New York.

01:33:49.630 --> 01:33:51.632
He was done
with bouncing around the world,

01:33:51.715 --> 01:33:54.801
and he just wanted to be back
in New York and be a New Yorker.

01:33:55.344 --> 01:33:56.470
Me and Adam soon followed

01:33:56.553 --> 01:33:58.722
so the three of us could pursue
our true passion,

01:33:58.805 --> 01:34:00.098
astrophysics.

01:34:00.766 --> 01:34:02.559
But that didn't really work out.

01:34:03.644 --> 01:34:05.145
Summer of '96.

01:34:05.687 --> 01:34:08.941
We're back home, living a grown-up version
of our high school days.

01:34:09.024 --> 01:34:11.485
Nothing to do but wander around,
trying to link up,

01:34:11.568 --> 01:34:16.031
hanging out with some new friends, hearing
some new music and making new music.

01:34:16.114 --> 01:34:19.493
It's not so much that we settled down.
It's more like we settled in.

01:34:20.077 --> 01:34:22.871
So after a couple years
of doing what we usually do,

01:34:22.955 --> 01:34:27.376
make music, order some food,
bullshit, hang out, make more music,

01:34:27.793 --> 01:34:29.211
we finished a record.

01:34:29.294 --> 01:34:31.880
And maybe our favorite,
'cause it's so experimental.

01:34:32.381 --> 01:34:33.423
Hello Nasty.

01:34:38.303 --> 01:34:42.266
And when we went on tour for that record,
it was the biggest tour we'd ever done.

01:34:42.933 --> 01:34:45.102
It's not that "Fight for Your Right
(To Party)" got erased,

01:34:45.727 --> 01:34:48.105
but at this point,
we were kinda fine without it.

01:34:48.897 --> 01:34:50.732
By that time, we were almost grown-ups.

01:34:51.275 --> 01:34:55.028
The beer and the dick
and the frat dudes were gone.

01:34:55.112 --> 01:34:56.989
You could barely see them anymore.

01:34:57.322 --> 01:34:58.991
By now we were a little older.

01:34:59.074 --> 01:35:02.452
We had other things to do separately,
like grown-up stuff.

01:35:02.536 --> 01:35:04.788
We were in serious relationships,
we had a record label,

01:35:04.872 --> 01:35:06.707
a magazine, a bicycle store,

01:35:06.999 --> 01:35:08.333
but the three of us made a life

01:35:08.417 --> 01:35:11.086
making records and touring
and playing shows together.

01:35:11.962 --> 01:35:15.883
It's not so much that we grew up.
It's more like we wised up.

01:35:17.050 --> 01:35:19.553
Now we can say that our reflection
on the mistakes we made

01:35:19.803 --> 01:35:23.098
came from Yauch
and the ideas that he brought back to us.

01:35:23.182 --> 01:35:24.433
But that's partly true.

01:35:24.516 --> 01:35:26.143
I mean, we were ready for change.

01:35:26.476 --> 01:35:29.605
We encouraged each other to do
and say what we wanted to do.

01:35:29.938 --> 01:35:32.524
If Yauch wanted to make a song called
"Bodhisattva Vow,"

01:35:32.608 --> 01:35:36.069
about a Buddhist vow to make
the world a better place, of course.

01:35:36.153 --> 01:35:37.362
That's fucking awesome.

01:35:39.615 --> 01:35:41.950
We have the maturity to realize

01:35:42.034 --> 01:35:44.578
that what we make and have made matters

01:35:44.661 --> 01:35:47.581
and affects people in good and bad ways.

01:35:47.664 --> 01:35:50.834
We're grateful that we've been around
long enough to comment on it.

01:35:50.918 --> 01:35:54.588
And we're lucky enough
to be able to do something about it now.

01:35:54.671 --> 01:35:59.176
There's a song on Hello Nasty called
"Song for the Man" that Adam wrote...

01:35:59.259 --> 01:36:01.762
Where are you? Adam wrote this one.

01:36:01.845 --> 01:36:06.141
...about the ways that so many men act
when a woman walks by.

01:36:06.225 --> 01:36:08.769
An interviewer called him out
as a hypocrite

01:36:08.852 --> 01:36:10.479
and challenged him about the song

01:36:10.562 --> 01:36:12.898
coming from
the "Fight for Your Right (To Party)" guy.

01:36:12.981 --> 01:36:15.108
And when I heard his answer,

01:36:15.192 --> 01:36:16.693
I was proud to be his friend.

01:36:17.528 --> 01:36:19.905
He said something like,

01:36:19.988 --> 01:36:23.242
"I'd rather be a hypocrite
than the same person forever."

01:36:29.373 --> 01:36:30.874
All right.

01:36:30.958 --> 01:36:32.876
I'm gonna tell you a story about--

01:36:32.960 --> 01:36:36.338
Well, I'm gonna tell you a story
from our book, Beastie Boys Book.

01:36:38.131 --> 01:36:39.049
All right.

01:36:40.008 --> 01:36:41.468
It's called, "The Last Gig."

01:36:47.975 --> 01:36:50.602
We didn't know it was gonna be
the last gig we'd ever play.

01:36:51.520 --> 01:36:54.314
Everything that happened that day
was totally normal.

01:36:54.398 --> 01:36:58.026
The gig was headlining a huge festival
in Tennessee called Bonnaroo.

01:36:58.110 --> 01:37:00.028
And it was 2009.

01:37:00.112 --> 01:37:02.865
Thousands and thousands of people
were gonna be there,

01:37:02.948 --> 01:37:04.533
and we were the headliner.

01:37:04.616 --> 01:37:06.785
We went down to Tennessee early,
'cause we were gonna shoot a video

01:37:06.869 --> 01:37:08.704
for a new song that hadn't come out yet.

01:37:08.787 --> 01:37:13.083
It was us, the rapper Nas,
and Roman Coppola was gonna direct it.

01:37:13.166 --> 01:37:16.378
It was oddly normal for us
to play these huge concerts

01:37:16.461 --> 01:37:19.173
and have someone like Roman
with a Bolex camera filming us

01:37:19.256 --> 01:37:21.675
running around supermarkets in Tennessee.

01:37:23.510 --> 01:37:26.388
The weirder,
the more normal for us by then.

01:37:30.142 --> 01:37:32.644
Things in life never come full circle.

01:37:33.478 --> 01:37:35.397
Maybe once or twice they're hexagonal,

01:37:35.480 --> 01:37:38.442
but to me they're almost always misshapen,

01:37:38.525 --> 01:37:41.570
as if drawn by a toddler in crayon.

01:37:42.529 --> 01:37:44.823
There's common threads, sure.

01:37:44.907 --> 01:37:47.034
Yauch and me and Mike are still together.

01:37:47.117 --> 01:37:49.036
Still laughing. Still family.

01:37:49.620 --> 01:37:53.248
Al Green was finishing his set
on one of the many stages at the festival,

01:37:53.332 --> 01:37:56.168
and so hearing his voice in the distance
was comforting.

01:37:56.251 --> 01:37:58.462
Just like how it was
when I was in high school,

01:37:58.545 --> 01:38:00.631
in my bedroom,
waiting for them to come over.

01:38:04.343 --> 01:38:07.012
But now was such a great distance
from that.

01:38:14.269 --> 01:38:17.689
The rearview
was nearly impossible to reposition.

01:38:18.982 --> 01:38:21.443
Kate Schellenbach wasn't there
with us in Tennessee.

01:38:21.527 --> 01:38:23.070
John Berry wasn't there.

01:38:23.153 --> 01:38:25.447
Dave Scilken, Bosco, the Captain,

01:38:25.948 --> 01:38:27.574
Dave Parsons, Mike's dad--

01:38:35.874 --> 01:38:37.876
Mike's dad, my mom, not there.

01:38:38.669 --> 01:38:39.711
So many more.

01:38:40.337 --> 01:38:43.298
Now me and Adam and Mike
were older, and we knew it.

01:38:43.382 --> 01:38:44.925
We were about to put out a new record,

01:38:45.008 --> 01:38:47.302
and we were still very much
in the game though.

01:38:47.386 --> 01:38:49.555
We were getting ready
to start all over again.

01:38:51.348 --> 01:38:56.562
Headlining a huge festival is very
different from a nice turnout at CBGBs.

01:38:57.813 --> 01:39:00.983
But shit, man. We didn't know it was
gonna be the last show we'd ever play.

01:39:06.655 --> 01:39:08.490
A major loss in the music business.

01:39:08.574 --> 01:39:12.953
Adam Yauch of the Beastie Boys
has died after a long fight with cancer.

01:39:13.036 --> 01:39:15.664
He was known as MCA,
and the three musicians together

01:39:15.747 --> 01:39:19.001
were among the few
at the vanguard of a movement.

01:39:19.084 --> 01:39:23.005
Yauch was a self-taught musician
and later a filmmaker.

01:39:23.088 --> 01:39:27.050
Adam Yauch, MCA, was 47 years old.

01:39:37.519 --> 01:39:39.897
I mean, we all have
different types of friends.

01:39:41.106 --> 01:39:43.400
There's the one
that's kind of an asshole...

01:39:44.484 --> 01:39:46.653
but fun to be around once in a while.

01:39:46.737 --> 01:39:48.655
Fun to get drunk and talk shit with,

01:39:48.739 --> 01:39:52.409
but you'd never actually call on them
for physical or emotional help

01:39:52.492 --> 01:39:54.328
'cause they're just unreliable.

01:39:54.411 --> 01:39:58.540
Or there's a friend you see
once in a while, and it's a nice hangout,

01:39:58.624 --> 01:39:59.791
and you're always like,

01:39:59.875 --> 01:40:01.960
"I should spend more time
with that person,"

01:40:02.044 --> 01:40:04.087
but for some reason, you just don't.

01:40:04.922 --> 01:40:06.256
Then there's that true friend,

01:40:06.340 --> 01:40:08.342
the one you'd
be on the phone with forever.

01:40:09.134 --> 01:40:12.095
The one that helps you move
or meets you at the hospital

01:40:12.179 --> 01:40:14.348
or has a permanent spot
on their couch for you

01:40:14.431 --> 01:40:16.391
just in case you'd ever need it.

01:40:17.309 --> 01:40:20.604
Now those types of friends are rare.
We all know.

01:40:20.687 --> 01:40:23.440
But there's an even rarer type of friend:

01:40:23.524 --> 01:40:25.442
The one that gets you motivated.

01:40:25.526 --> 01:40:27.361
The one that not only
gets themselves going

01:40:27.444 --> 01:40:29.196
and doing great things,

01:40:29.279 --> 01:40:32.407
but says, "We should all
get together and do this."

01:40:32.491 --> 01:40:34.535
And then does it.

01:40:34.618 --> 01:40:36.578
Adam Yauch was that type of friend.

01:40:45.045 --> 01:40:47.339
A once-in-a-lifetime type of friend.

01:40:47.965 --> 01:40:50.217
The friend that makes it happen.

01:40:50.300 --> 01:40:52.678
The friend that inspires you to go big.

01:40:54.012 --> 01:40:56.723
Can we turn this up? This is a song
that Yauch wrote for Hello Nasty.

01:41:01.103 --> 01:41:06.483
Now around 1990, Yauch went to India,
Nepal and met Tibetans in exile.

01:41:06.567 --> 01:41:09.528
And he wanted to understand
their vow of nonviolence.

01:41:10.445 --> 01:41:13.323
Why did they choose not to fight back
against the government

01:41:13.407 --> 01:41:16.827
that would beat and imprison a person
just for waving a Tibetan flag?

01:41:16.910 --> 01:41:18.370
He wanted to know more.

01:41:18.453 --> 01:41:20.163
He wanted to help.

01:41:20.247 --> 01:41:21.707
But in typical Yauch fashion,

01:41:21.790 --> 01:41:23.959
instead of just writing a check
to some organization,

01:41:24.042 --> 01:41:25.127
he started his own.

01:41:25.210 --> 01:41:26.753
The Milarepa Fund.

01:41:29.631 --> 01:41:32.384
And he organized the first
Tibetan Freedom Concert.

01:41:32.467 --> 01:41:34.261
A massive two-day benefit concert

01:41:34.344 --> 01:41:38.724
in Golden Gate Park
in San Francisco in 1996.

01:41:40.100 --> 01:41:43.270
It was the biggest charity concert
since Live Aid.

01:41:43.353 --> 01:41:45.022
What he did was historic.

01:41:45.105 --> 01:41:48.483
Hundreds of thousands of people
had "Free Tibet" on their tongues

01:41:48.567 --> 01:41:50.485
and on their bumper stickers.

01:41:50.569 --> 01:41:52.863
They heard the call for nonviolence

01:41:52.946 --> 01:41:55.782
all because of that guy in Beastie Boys.

01:41:55.866 --> 01:41:57.576
I mean, who does that?

01:42:03.665 --> 01:42:06.418
Yauch, Mike and I
have spent more time with each other

01:42:06.502 --> 01:42:07.836
than with our own families.

01:42:07.920 --> 01:42:09.004
Really.

01:42:09.087 --> 01:42:11.131
So when it comes to my friend
the rapper Mike D,

01:42:11.215 --> 01:42:14.843
AKA Sweet Lou, AKA Michael Louis Diamond,

01:42:14.927 --> 01:42:16.553
I know him, right?

01:42:16.637 --> 01:42:17.679
Like, everything.

01:42:17.763 --> 01:42:19.348
And he knows me just the same.

01:42:19.431 --> 01:42:22.184
But Adam Yauch, a puzzle.

01:42:22.267 --> 01:42:23.435
A conundrum.

01:42:24.645 --> 01:42:26.480
Finish up. I can't.

01:42:26.563 --> 01:42:29.233
A labyrinth of ideas and emotions.

01:42:29.316 --> 01:42:31.652
An enigma, a wild card.

01:42:31.735 --> 01:42:34.530
And after 35 years of friendship,

01:42:34.613 --> 01:42:38.492
I never knew
what he was gonna do or say next.

01:42:38.575 --> 01:42:41.453
He was a living contradiction
of people's ideas

01:42:41.537 --> 01:42:45.791
of how or what
you're supposed to be or do.

01:42:46.625 --> 01:42:48.710
I mean,
he's the Buddhist guy who's telling me

01:42:48.794 --> 01:42:53.173
how last night he was at this
after-after party for some fashion show.

01:42:53.924 --> 01:42:56.802
And he's the
"Fight for Your Right (To Party)" dude

01:42:56.885 --> 01:43:00.138
who went trekking through Nepal
on some kind of discovery quest.

01:43:00.222 --> 01:43:03.016
And then he met with politicians
in Washington, DC,

01:43:03.100 --> 01:43:06.478
letting them know what he'd seen
and what he learned.

01:43:13.819 --> 01:43:17.573
